<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNITA Forces Chased out of W. Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- An Angolan government official
revealed here Monday that forces of the rebel National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) have been chased out of
the western part of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and are
now in Uige Province in north Angola.
</P>
<P>
According to Cordeiro Ernesto Sacundomba, governor of Uige
Province, some UNITA militiamen had been evacuated from western
DRC under strong military pressure from DRC government army.
</P>
<P>
They then crossed into Uige through floating bridges they set
up over Ambriz River near Mbanza Congo, capital of Zaire Province.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA forces led by its Chairman Jonas Savimbi was the ally
of the DRC rebels fighting to overthrow President Laurent Kabila's
government. The Angolan government, however, also sent a
7,000-strong troops to support Kabila so as to contain UNITA's
possible attack from the neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
The governor expressed worries that with the return of UNITA
forces to the north, the relative tranquility could be once again
broken and the province might become yet another tension area.
</P>
<P>
At present, UNITA forces are mainly concentrated in Huambo and
Bie provinces in central Angola and Malanje Province in the north,
fighting with government army.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the UNITA soldiers have been chased back by
Angolan troops in the DRC, for the government of the vast central
African country does not have strong armed forces.
</P>
<P>
It is indicated that since government army suffered setbacks in
central Angola, it intends to recall its troops in the DRC to the
civil war.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of Angola, Zimbabwe, Namibia and the DRC held a
summit here on April 8, and discussed mainly the military
cooperation in the Angolan conflict. Later, Kabila accepted the
ceasefire initiative with the rebels and signed a peace agreement
with Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni in Surte, Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
