<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Pardons 4,000 Inmates on Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has pardoned more than 4,000 inmates who were left
with three months to complete their jail terms on the occasion of
the country's Union Day.
</P>
<P>
The presidential clemency, however, will not benefit those who
were convicted of illegal possession of fire arms, drug
trafficking, car theft, robbery, sexual harrassment, a statement
released by the Tanzania Information Services said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Others who will not be pardoned include those who had once
escaped or tried to break prisons and those who were convicted of
bribery.
</P>
<P>
"It is the hope of the government that those to benefit from
the pardon would be law-abiding citizens," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, to remember the historical event of the union
between Tanganyika and Zanzibar, which formed the United Republic
of Tanzania 35 years ago, President Mkapa inspected Monday a guard
of honor at the the National Stadium in the capital Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The parade was mounted by the Tanzania People's Defense Forces
(TPDF), which drew applauses and ululations from tens of thousands
of Dar es Salaam residents who thronged to the stadium to
celebrate the event.
</P>
<P>
Among the national leaders who attended the annual event were
Tanzanian Vice-President Omar Ali Juma, the President of Zanzibar,
Salmin Amour, Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye, and the Speaker of
the National Assembly, Pius Msekwa.
</P>
<P>
Congratulatory messages have poured into Tanzania from Burundi,
Denmark, Romania, Guinea, Japan, Cyprus, Senegal and other
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
