<HEADLINE> Egypt Never Acts Against Sudan: Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa on Monday underlined that his country maintains special
ties with Sudan, saying that Cairo "never acts against" Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt will never act against Sudan," Moussa told reporters,
saying that Egypt is keen on helping solve Sudan's problems in a
positive way and supports its sovereignty, unity and territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
Moussa was responding to Sudanese President Omar Hassan Ahmed
al-Bashir's recent statement on Sudanese-Egyptian relations.
Al-Bashir also called on Egypt to extradite the Sudanese
opposition to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Egypt keeps contacts with Sudan's opposition both in the Muslim
north and the Christian south. It has voiced support for Sudan's
integrity, fearing that a possible partition of the country would
endanger the Nile, its main water source.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that al-Bashir's statements also included
assurances of the importance and the pivotal nature of the special
relations between Egypt and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt welcomes this part of the statements," Moussa said,
expressing hope that the Egyptian-Sudanese relations will develop
in a smooth way.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt works for protecting the territorial integrity of Sudan,
its people and land, as this is the framework of the Egyptian
policy towards Sudan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Egypt and Sudan soured in 1995 after
Cairo accused Khartoum of masterminding an assassination attempt
on President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Egypt also blamed Sudan for harboring Islamic militants, who
have been fighting since 1992 against the Egyptian government in
an attempt to install a strict Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has denied both charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
