<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Urged to Comment on Draft Broadcasting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian parliament, the
House of People's Representatives, Monday called on all pertinent
bodies in the country to actively participate in the public
hearing on the draft broadcasting proclamation scheduled for
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Ahmed Hussein, chairman of
media and culture committee of the house, also urged all pertinent
bodies to comment on the draft broadcasting proclamation.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Ahmed said various
religious institutions as well as other bodies concerned are
expressing their views on the bill.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian parliament discussed the draft broadcasting
proclamation at its regular session last March and referred it for
further scrutiny to its legal affairs standing committee.
</P>
<P>
The draft proclamation that provides for the systematic
management of broadcasting services in the country will enable the
establishment of private radio and television (TV) stations.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, political parties, religious
organizations and non-Ethiopians would not be licensed to
undertake broadcasting services in the country, Ahmed said, adding
that "license issued for radio and TV stations shall remain in
force for eight and ten years respectively."
</P>
<P>
There is only one TV station in Ethiopia, that is the Ethiopian
TV which is established by the government. There are several
radio stations which have been established by the federal
government and state governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
