<HEADLINE> Africa to Be Fully Integrated into World Economy, U.N.  Africa Chief Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.N. official on African
affairs Monday voiced her confidence that "Africa will become
fully integrated into the world economy."
</P>
<P>
Thelma Awori, assistant administrator of the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) and director of UNDP's Africa Bureau,
told a luncheon here that "With enhanced trade and investment,
UNDP is confident that Africa will become fully integrated into
the world economy, offering a promise of hope and future to its
youth."
</P>
<P>
"Africa today is united by a shared vision of collective
self-reliance for peace and sustainable development," she said,
"It is also determined to fully integrate itself into the global
village, as a more active partner."
</P>
<P>
"Translating Africa's vision into concrete actions requires
capacity building not only in Africa but of those who are partners
of Africa," she said.
</P>
<P>
"One such capacity is the capacity to rely on the wisdom and
commitment of Africans to regenerate the environment, create
employment, advance the status of women, promote transparent and
accountable governance and in so doing to create wealth, " she
said.
</P>
<P>
"UNDP counts on the private sector as a strategic partner in
supporting Africa in achieving these ends," she said.
</P>
<P>
Awori made the remarks at a luncheon during the five-day
"Attracting Capital to Africa Summit", which began here on
Saturday last week.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, UNDP began a workshop on "Financial
Intermediation and Private Sector in Africa" to analyze the
problems of the private sector and suggest approaches to help
Africa deepen its financial mediation and attract foreign direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
UNDP also co-organized the State of Connecticut Africa Business
Conference 1999 with the State Government on April 20-21 as part
of an effort to ensure global competitiveness of African
enterprises and entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
"For me, the Connecticut conference and the Houston Summit are
symbols of the new form of cooperation and partnership that we at
UNDP plan to continue to encourage -- a partnership of mutual
respect and mutual benefit," Awori added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley also took the floor at
the luncheon, saying that the U.S. trade with Africa can serve the
interest of the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
