<HEADLINE> S. African Countries Meet on Malaria Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 26 (Xinhua) -- With the support of the World
Health Organization (WHO), southern African countries met here
Monday on eliminating malaria.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting will focus on effectively elimination of
malaria in Africa through strategies closer to the African reality
in accordance with the WHO Roll Back Malaria program.
</P>
<P>
The Roll Back Malaria program which was initiated last year is
aimed at both eliminating malaria and supporting the development
of health systems in countries affected by this disease.
</P>
<P>
A WHO report showed that about 1.5 million to 2.7 million
people in the world die of malaria every year, among them at least
one million are children under five years.
</P>
<P>
Those affected by the disease are mainly living in countries
with poor health conditions, especially in sub-Saharan Africa,
which has brought negative impact on the countries' ecomony.
</P>
<P>
A report released at the meeting said malaria is spreading
around the world, particularly to areas which used to be believed
as unaffected by the disease.
</P>
<P>
The meeting calls for long-term plans and measures to contain
and root out the disease.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be closed Thursday, has drawn representatives
from South Africa, Angola, Botswana, Malawi, Namibia, Swaziland,
Zambia, Zimbabwe, Sao Tome &AMP; Principe and Seychelles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
