<HEADLINE> Govt Army Defeats UNITA Attack in C. Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- An Angolan military source
announced here Monday that the government army is still in control
of Cunhinga in the central province of Bie after defeating the
counter-attack launched Sunday by the rebel National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) at the strategic town.
</P>
<P>
According to the source from the Defense Ministry, UNITA forces
had mobilized tanks and cannons during the attack. However, they
suffered " severe casualties" at the resistance of government
army.
</P>
<P>
The army also destroyed five BMP-2 armored personnel vehicles
and obtained a large number of weapons and ammunitions. But the
source did not reveal the loss on the side of government army.
</P>
<P>
Cunhinga was about 30 kilometers from Kuito, capital of Bie.
To prevent the city's airport from being attacked, the government
army recovered the town for the second time on April 11. The
first was in early this year.
</P>
<P>
According to another report, at least 25 people including 10
policemen were killed and wounded many others in an attack on a
train on Sunday near Canjala, some 80 kms from the western port
city of Benguela in western Angola.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA troops were possibly responsible for the attack.
</P>
<P>
The radio said in another report that 11 people had died when a
convoy of lorries was ambushed, also near Benguela.
</P>
<P>
It did not say when the attack occurred and possibly the two
reports were referring to the same incident.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities were searching the area for more bodies and
possible survivors of the attack on the train carrying food
supplies, the second in two weeks, said the radio.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, 15 people died in the same place when civilian
vehicles were ambushed, it added.
</P>
<P>
Road and rail ambushes have become frequent since fighting
resumed in last December between forces loyal to the government of
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and UNITA rebels just before
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The civil war has since spread across much of the impoverished
southern African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
