<HEADLINE> Clinton Suggests Three-Way Mideast Summit This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton Monday
called for a three-day summit meeting with Israeli and Palestinian
leaders within six months after Israel holds election in May to
complete the land-for security deal he helped bring about last
October.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart issued the call for both
sides to work out a framework to revive peace talks running
aground late last year because of Israel's refusal to withdraw
from more part of the West Bank, stipulated by the Wye accord
approved last October by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat under the brokerage of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"If Israel and the Palestinians are to reach an agreement, it
is essential that they do their part to create a serious, fair and
credible environment for negotiations," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's call urged Netanyahu and Arafat to adhere to the
commitments they made in the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
These commitments include an Israeli promise to give up more
land on the West Bank and a Palestinian pledge to root out
terrorists in areas already under Arafat control.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has disagreed publicly with Israel,
saying that while the Palestinians had done fairly well, there was
an obligation on Israel to pull back as promised from 13.1 percent
of the West Bank territory, which, however, was completed only by
2 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has said several times that if he did not gain statehood
through negotiations, he would declare a state unilaterally after
May 4.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has urged the Palestinian leader not to make any
announcement of creating a Palestinian state before the Israeli
election scheduled on May 17, for fear it would make the present
impasse even worse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
