<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Emir Invites Jordanian King for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Emir Jaber Al-Ahmed
Al-Sabah Monday invited Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein to
visit his emirate for the first time since the 1990 Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was conveyed to Abdullah by Kuwaiti Minister of
Justice and Islamic Affairs Ahmad Khaled Al-Kulaib, who is in
Amman to discuss bilateral cooperation in legal and judicial
fields.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Jaber invited Abdullah to visit Kuwait as early
as possible and stressed that the best way to consolidate
bilateral ties and to coordinate Arab stands on regional issues
is a ``direct meeting`` between Abdullah and himself.
</P>
<P>
Jaber's invitation to Abdullah is the first of its kind in nine
years since the 1990 Gulf Crisis which was triggered by Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait suspended its diplomatic ties with Jordan and expelled
some 200,000 Jordanian workers during the crisis because Amman
was sympathetic with Baghdad after Iraqi troops stormed into the
tiny Gulf emirate.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian-Kuwaiti ties began to thaw since 1995 when Amman
apparently distanced itself from Baghdad and called for political
changes in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
And the two countries normalized ties in March 1999 when
Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel-Ilah al-Khatib paid an official
visit to Kuwait and reopened the Jordanian embassy there.
</P>
<P>
Currently Jordan has been trying to strike a delicate balance
between Iraq and Kuwait because it still relies on Iraq as its
only source for cheap crude oil and oil products.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government claimed on many occasions that it
would maintain friendly ties with all neighbors and would not
improve ties with one country at the expense of another. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
