<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Repentant Extremists Set Free in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 26 (Xinhua) -- An unspecified number of detainees,
suspected members of Islamic extremist groups, were set free on
Monday in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry released the detainees after they have
renounced extremism and violence, a security official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Islamic militants began an insurgency in 1992 in an attempt to
topple Egypt's secular government and install a strict Islamic
rule. About 1,200 people, mostly police and militants, have been
killed in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Under the emergency law, which took effect in 1981 after the
assassination of President Anwar Sadat, Egyptian police are
empowered to detain those believed to be endangering public
security.
</P>
<P>
The release of the repentant extremists came amid reports of an
alleged deal between the government and the Islamic Group, the
country's largest militant group, in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The security official dismissed the reports as "groundless,"
saying that "legitimacy is unnegotiable. Security agencies are
unwavering in their fighting against terrorism." 
</P>
</TEXT>
