<HEADLINE> Ugandan's Life Expectancy Lowest in E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan enjoy the lowest life
expectancy in East Africa because its relatively low social
indicators over the past three decades, a senor World Bank
official told Xinhua here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Randolph Harris, World Bank's resident representative in
Uganda, said although Uganda's economic growth rate is among the
highest in the world, its social indicators were low in the past.
</P>
<P>
A World Bank report entitled World Development Indicators 1999
launched Monday in Washington D.C., the United States, showed that
average life expectancy for Ugandans is 42 years, much lower than
that for Tanzanians (48) and Kenyans (52).
</P>
<P>
The official attributed this low life expectancy to, among
other things, Uganda's armed conflicts in the 70s and 80s, adding
that wars not only cost young lives but also damaged a lot of
health facilities across the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the National Resistance Movement came to power in 1986,
Uganda has benefited from relative stable society and sustained
economic growth. However, this cannot push Uganda's average life
expectancy up to the level of Kenya, Harris noted.
</P>
<P>
With surging national economy, social infrastructure has been
improving in recent years. But achievement can be easily wiped
out by rampant spreading of HIV/AIDS and the widening gap between
the rich and poor, he warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
