<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Remains Problem for Developing Countries: WB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Washington, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Poverty remains a serious
problem for the developing countries, a World Bank report released
here Monday said.
</P>
<P>
All developing regions have lost momentum in achieving their
poverty reduction goals, the report said.
</P>
<P>
During the period 1990-97, East and South Asia were the only
regions growing fast enough to reduce poverty by half by 2015.
</P>
<P>
Current forecasts for 1998-2001 suggest that only South Asia
and China will grow sufficiently to achieve this goal, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The most dramatic loss has been for East Asian countries.
Comparing their latest growth forecasts with those from just 12
months ago, the average number of years it will take to reduce
poverty by 10 percent, as required by the international
development goals agreed several years ago, has risen by roughly
two years for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, where income growth has historically been
low, its slowdown in growth will increase the time it takes to
meet its poverty target by as much as 10 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
