<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Digital Age Expands Reach of Global Knowledge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- According to World Development
Indicators 1999, the communications and computer revolutions are
greatly expanding the reach of global knowledge, said a World Bank
report released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
They can allow developing countries to leapfrog old
technologies that still hold sway in industrial countries, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of cellular to total mainframe telephone use is much
higher in the Philippines and Sri Lanka than in Belgium or France.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide, Finland has the greatest number of cellular phones
per 1,000 people with 417; followed by Norway with 381; Sweden
with 358; Japan with 303; and Israel with 283.
</P>
<P>
The report also shows that Sub-Saharan Africa countries such as
Botswana, Djibouti, and Ghana have 100 percent digital telephone
networks, compared with the OECD (Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development) average of less than 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although the Internet continues to reach millions of new
subscribers each year in both developed and developing countries,
the report shows that industrial countries, particularly those in
Scandinavia, continue to have the greatest access to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
As with cellular technology, Finland also has the world's
largest number of Internet hosts per 10,000 people with 996;
followed by the United States with 976; Norway with 705; New
Zealand with 468; and Sweden with 430. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
