<HEADLINE> NATO Official: No Force Used to Halt Oil to Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- A top official of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) said on Monday that the allied
naval force will not use force when attempting to halt oil
shipment to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters one day after the three-day alliance
summit, German General Klaus Naumann, who commands NATO's Military
Committee said that the oil blockade regime against Yugoslavia
will not "give us the right to force" any ship to abandon its
course.
</P>
<P>
"So we cannot stop a merchant vessel by the use of force," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Naumann said that NATO's Military Committee was likely to
approve an implementation plan in Belgium on Monday or Tuesday for
warships to begin searching vessels headed for Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
With an aim to block the oil shipment into Yugoslavia, the
European Union and NATO have approved an oil embargo against the
country.
</P>
<P>
Naumann noted that the United Nations had not approved such an
embargo, and Russia vowed again on Monday that it would continue
oil shipments under contract to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously this is going to be addressed on an urgent basis,"
NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said at a separate briefing in
Washington on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Naumann insisted hat the inspection regime would still have a
dampening effect on imports of foreign oil into Yugoslavia through
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
"And all naval people tell me if you establish something like
this, third nations' ships will get very, very cautious -- they
will think twice whether they will take this route, because no one
likes to be stopped at sea by a warship," the general said.
</P>
</TEXT>
