<HEADLINE> "UNDP Needs to Do More to Change Image of Americans on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- "The workshop is held to give
feasibility to more creative thinking on the issue of financial
intermediation in Africa," a senior U.N. official said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Thelma Awori, assistant
administrator of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and
director of the agency's Africa Bureau, said that "UNDP needs to
do more to change the image that Americans have of the African
private sector."
</P>
<P>
Awori chaired a workshop, sponsored by UNDP, Monday on
"Financial Intermediation and Private Sector in Africa," part of
22 worships held during the five-day 1999 "Attracting Capital to
Africa Summit," which began here on Saturday last week.
</P>
<P>
"This is an important issue because our private sector is so
young, we need to have access to services outside capital cities,
we need to have structures in place in our countries that will
really improve the efficiency of our banking and financial
management," she said.
</P>
<P>
On the role of UNDP in promoting African development, she said,
"UNDP really facilitates very much developmental work. We have
been playing a major role in trying to get the American private
sector to understand the African private sector a bit more, to be
more comfortable with the African private sector."
</P>
<P>
"What we see is that we need to do more to change the image
that Americans have of the African private sector, and I think we
are making progress," she said, citing Botswana, Namibia, Ghana
and Cote d'Ivoire as "success stories in Africa."
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, Americans saw Africa as a continent full of
poverty and conflicts, not aware of the economic progress made by
southern African countries, such as Botswana, Mozimbique and
Namibia, which enjoy political stability, conducive to economic
and social development.
</P>
<P>
UNDP convened the workshop, expected to last two days here, to
analyze the problems of the private sector and suggest approaches
to help Africa deepen its financial mediation and attract foreign
direct investment.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, UNDP also co-organized the State of Connecticut Africa
Business Conference 1999 with the State Government on April 20-21
as part of an effort to ensure global competitiveness of African
enterprises and entrepreneurs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
