<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Investments in Africa Generate Higher Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. direct investments in
Sub-Saharan Africa have generated higher returns than in many
other regions, according to U.S. Department of Commerce on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a backgrounder prepared for Attracting Capital to Africa
Summit, now being held here, the Department said U.S. direct
investments in Sub-Saharan Africa generated net income of 1.5
billion U.S. dollars in 1997, the latest year the data are
available.
</P>
<P>
The 22 percent return against book value compares with 11
percent in Europe, 12 percent in Latin America, 13 percent in
Asia-Pacific, 17 percent in the Middle East and 12 percent
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
During the 1992-96 period, the average annual return of the
U.S. direct investments in Africa was 28.7 percent, more than
2-1/2 times the average return rate of U.S. investments
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
At year-end 1997, the U.S. direct investments position in
Sub-Saharan Africa stood at 7.1 billion dollars, a 58 percent rise
over 1996, led by growing capital outflows from U.S. parent
companies to their affiliates in South Africa and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Despite strong growth in the direct investments, Sub-Saharan
Africa accounted for less than 1 percent of the U.S. position
worldwide in 1997.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, Nigeria and Angola combined to account for nearly
two-thirds of the U.S. direct investment position in Sub-Saharan
Africa in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. position in Nigeria and Angola is heavily concentrated
in the petroleum sector, while in South Africa is largely in
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
U.N. data show that Africa attracted total FDI flows of 19.2
billion dollars in the period 1982-96. The United States was the
third leading supplier of FDI to Africa, providing 16.9 percent of
total flows.
</P>
<P>
Britain led all supplers with 25.9 percent, followed by France,
24.6 percent, Germany, 7.2 percent, Japan, 5.7 percent and the
Netherlands, 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. World Investment Report 1998 said Africa accounts for
only 3 percent of total FDI flows to developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
