<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Awori Directs UNDP Africa Program Differently (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- "We have to learn to use the
immense capacities in Africa, to recognize what people are doing
and see how best we can support it, rather than coming in with our
own agenda and our own ideas of what people should do," said Ms.
Thelma Awori, assistant administrator of the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) and director of the U.N. agency's
Africa Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Awori is among participants at the current conference, titled
"Attracting Capital to Africa Summit", which kicked off here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP's Africa Bureau on Monday morning began a workshop on
"Financial Intermediation and Private Sector in Africa" at the
five-day summit to analyze the problems of the private sector and
suggest approaches to help Africa deepen its financial mediation
and attract direct investment.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to use the event to generate new ideas and concrete
proposals on how to make the African private sector the engine of
of economic growth," she said.
</P>
<P>
Broad experience has made Awori a firm believer in popular
participation in the development process. A Ugandan of Liberian
origin and a former university lecturer, she has long been an
activist in the women's movement.
</P>
<P>
Awori was appointed to hold the current post in the U.N. system
in September 1997. Before joining UNDP, she worked extensively in
community mobilization and human resource development.
</P>
<P>
From 1988 to 1992, she was chief of the Africa Section and then
deputy director of the UNDP affiliate, the U.N. Development Fund
for Women (UNIFEM). She then served as U.N. Resident Coordinator
and UNDP Resident Representative in Zimbabwe until 1996 before
returning to New York as deputy director of UNDP's Policy and
Program Support Bureau.
</P>
<P>
With a perspective stretching from community activities to
international policy-making, Awori has done a lot to advance UNDP
efforts to achieve "national execution" of development program.
Facing a worrying decline in development aid, African countries
have to use all available resources in the most effective and
sustainable ways, she said.
</P>
<P>
This means strengthening local ability to coordinate, manage,
monitor and evaluate external aid, and making greater use of local
expertise. Development work, she said, "should go beyond the
donor/ recipient relationship and become a true partnership."
</P>
<P>
With UNDP a major, but far from the only, source of development
finances, Awori sees the need for greater coherence. She expects
the Resident Coordinator system and the U.N. Development Group
proposed in the U.N. Secretary-General's reforms to strengthen
partnerships with other donors and make the broader donor
community "as user-friendly as possible to host governments."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Awori Directs UNDP Africa Program Differently (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- But in many cases, the African
continent afford the "unbearably high moral, economic, social and
political costs" of excluding "a huge segment of our society" from
the development process, she said.
</P>
<P>
Exclusion is the main cause of poverty and conflict throughout
Africa, she said, adding that this makes "inclusion the key
development challenge of our time," she said and dictates an
urgent agenda of human and institutional development.
</P>
<P>
"As I travel across Africa, I see a continent that is proud of
its history, culture, and abundance of natural and human assets,"
she said. "I see a continent that is beginning to look to itself
for answers."
</P>
<P>
In February this year, Awori attended a meeting in Cotonou,
Benin, where 45 UNDP Resident Representatives in African countries
reviewed Africa's development needs for the new millenium.
</P>
<P>
UNDP is one of the most widely implanted development agencies
in Africa. With a network of 45 country offices, UNDP focuses on
critical issues ranging from poverty, gender equality and the
empowerment of women to good governance and private sector
development.
</P>
<P>
Apart from better economic management and good governance in
Africa, Awori also attached importance to the linkages between
other priority areas for UNDP in Africa, such as poverty
eradication and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Awori is chairperson of the African Women in Crisis (AFWIC)
project, launched in 1993 by UNIFEM. The project has helped
refugee and displaced women prepare to return home by providing
reproductive health care, trauma counselling, and training and
development of skills.
</P>
<P>
"The women took over, declaring that they would no longer be
caught in conflict situations as victims," she said. "We had to
organize ourselves to support all these different groups of women
getting involved in conflict resolution, a movement which took off
like wildfire."
</P>
<P>
Awori is married to a Ugandan diplomat and has raised five
children. "Every women I know in Africa balances career
responsibilities with those she has in the family and the
community because of her gender. Like all women, we just have to
do it all." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
