<HEADLINE> Five Zambian Surveyors Detained by DRC Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Five Zambian surveyors have been
picked up and detained by government soldiers of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC), Zambia News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The five were picked up by heavily armed DRC soldiers last
Saturday morning from the Zambian side of Kasumbalesa border post
near Chililabombwe in Copperbelt province, north of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The Zambians were on routine work following the border line in
the bush when the Congolese pounced and dragged them into their
country, the news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The captives are accused of carrying out surveillance
activities for the rebels fighting to topple that country's
government led by President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Of the five, three are surveyors for Konkola division of the
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), and the others are
Ndola-based government surveyors.
</P>
<P>
Chililabombwe district senior security and defense officers
spend the whole day trying to seek their release but failed.
</P>
<P>
"We held a lengthy meeting today with Congolese officials to
try and seek the release of the Zambians but efforts bore no
fruition," a senior Zambia soldier said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
