<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: U.S.-African Trade Profile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Two-way trade between the United
States and Sub-Saharan Africa declined 12 percent in 1998,
according to U.S. Department of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume dropped to 19.8 billion U.S. dollars from 22.5
billion dollars in 1997, the Department said in a backgrounder
prepared for the current Attracting Capital to Africa Summit.
</P>
<P>
The April 24-28 Summit is being held here as a high-level forum
for African leaders and the U.S. business community to exchange
views to expand two-way trade and U.S. investment in Africa.
</P>
<P>
U.S. exports to the region rose to 6.69 billion dollars last
year from 6.17 billion dollars in 1997 while imports fell to 13.1
billion dollars from 16.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. share of Africa's total import market fell to 6.1
percent in 1997, the latest year for which data are available,
from 7.3 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Yet the U.S. moved up from third place to second among Africa's
industrial country suppliers.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, France topped the list with a market share of 6.5
percent, though declining from 11.1 percent in 1996. Britain
yielded from second place to third with a market share of 5.8
percent from 7.4 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
U.S. exports to Sub-Saharan Africa in 1998 reached their
highest total of 6.69 billion dollars, an increase of 8.4 percent
from 1997.
</P>
<P>
The exports expansion contrasted with declines in U.S.
shipments elsewhere when U.S. worldwide exports fell 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Despite growth in U.S. exports in 1998, Sub-Saharan Africa
accounted for less than 1 percent of total U.S. exports in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured exports comprised 72 percent. Principal U.S.
exports included aircraft, oil and gas equipment, construction
machinery, wheat, computers, motor vehicles and telecommunications
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Sales of telecommunications equipment grew 38 percent and motor
vehicles sales grew 27 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
U.S. purchases from Sub-Saharan Africa fell 20 percent in 1997
due to sharply lower world prices for crude oil, diamonds and
materials.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil accounted for 7.6 billion dollars, or 58 percent of
U.S. imports from the region.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Saharan Africa shared 20 percent by value of U.S. market
for crude oil, with Nigeria and Angola as major suppliers.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. imports about as much crude oil from Sub-Saharan
Africa as from the Persian Gulf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Closes Border Post with DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Monday closed its border
with the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) at Kasumbalesa near
Chililabombwe in the north of Zambia following the abduction of
five of its citizens last Saturday by DRC government soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The border was closed this morning by Zambian officials to
press for the return of the detained Zambians, according to Zambia
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The decision to close the border was reached by district
defense and security chiefs, who were said to be fed up with the
conduct of the Congolese authorities about the continued detention
of the Zambians.
</P>
<P>
A Zambian government team held a series of lengthy talks with
their Congolese counterparts since Saturday to seek the release of
the Zambians but failed.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, the border is closed. It was sealed this morning and no
one including vehicles are entering Congo," said Paul Ngoma,
police officer-in- charge in Chililabombwe.
</P>
<P>
However, it is not clear whether the decision to close the
border had the blessing of the central government of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
A long queue of heavy-duty international trucks carrying goods
to Congo were seen marooned on the Zambian side. A similar
situation obtained on the Congolese side of the border.
</P>
<P>
"Since the Zambians were picked up at Kasumbalesa border post
on the Zambian side, we have held a series of meetings with our
Congolese counterparts on the detainees. Each time we're assured
of their release soon, the Congolese come up with other flimsy
charges just to complicate the issue. We're fed up with this," a
defense officer told the news agency.
</P>
<P>
The five were on duty checking the border line west of
Kasumbalesa barrier when the armed soldiers from the country
pounced on them and dragged them into their side, it reported.
</P>
<P>
The five were accused of making reconnaissance for the rebels
fighting to topple DRC President Laurent Kabila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
