<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Holds Workshop on Financial Intermediation in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. agency on Monday morning
began a workshop here on "Financial Intermediation and Private
Sector in Africa" to analyze the problems of the private sector
and suggest approaches to help Africa deepen its financial
mediation and attract foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
The Africa Bureau of the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) sponsored the workshop on the sidelines of the five-day
"Attracting Capital to Africa Summit," which began here on
Saturday last week.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to use the event to generate new ideas and concrete
proposals on how to make the African private sector the engine of
economic growth," said Thelma Awori, assistant administrator of
UNDP and director of the U.N. agency's Africa Bureau.
</P>
<P>
"The private sector has an important role to play in Africa,"
said Awori, who chaired the workshop drawing representatives from
African and European countries.
</P>
<P>
"We are here to discuss what kind of assistance do we need to
put in place, and what kind o structure do we need to put in
place," she said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, part of 22 workshops held during the summit,
draws representatives from African and European countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Abdoulaye Mar Dieye, UNDP's chief economist, told
the workshop that Africa today faces challenges of a new global
environment, which include maintaining a competitive economy,
attracting capital and preventing capital flight.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet the challenges, it is very important for
African countries to work hard for the determined pursuit of sound
economic policies, regional and sub-regional cooperation,
favorable political atmosphere and increasing domestic savings and
investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Five heads of state, four prime ministers and high-level
representatives of some 30 African countries met with
entrepreneurs and chief executive officials of some of America's
largest corporation here on April 24-28 to discuss the state of
the private sector in Africa and the prospects for its
development.
</P>
<P>
The gathering, the second in the United States since 1997, is
also expected to explore opportunities for two-way trade and
investment between Africa and the United States. The first such
meeting was held in April 1997 in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
UNDP also co-organized the State of Connecticut Africa Business
Conference 1999 with the State Government on April 20-21 as part
of an effort to ensure global competitiveness of African
enterprises and entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
The current summit follows the heals of the U.S.-Africa
Ministerial Meetings held in Washington last month. The two events
are seen as an integral part of the redefinition of the U.S. ties
with Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
