<HEADLINE> German Main Opposition Rejects Kosovo Ground Troop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN April 26 (Xinhua)--The Christian Democratic Union (CDU),
Germany's main opposition, rejected sending ground combat troops
to Kosovo Monday at the party's congress in Erfurt.
</P>
<P>
A statement approved by the 1,000 delegates said, "the CDU will
not approve any step which could trigger uncontrollable military
developments in the Balkan region."
</P>
<P>
"There must not be any uncontrolled, automatic escalation (in
Kosovo)," CDU chairman and parliamentary fraction chief Wolfgang
Schaeuble said at the congress overshadowed by the Kosovo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We must not cross the red line, " CDU deputy chairman and
former Defence Minister Volker Rueher told the delegates.
</P>
<P>
The party leaders also called for any deployment of the German
forces under NATO mandate, including humanitarian deployment, to
be passed by German parliament at first.
</P>
<P>
The German government has sent without parliament's approval
some 400 soldiers and 7 helicopters to Albania as pioneers of a
NATO humanitarian troop.
</P>
<P>
Although the CDU backed the cabinet's decision of sending 14
Tornado jet fighters to participate in the NATO air strikes
against Yugoslavia, the party executives at the congress demanded
a political solution to the crisis under closer cooperation with
Russia and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The CDU leaders criticized that cabinet heads' harsh words
against Yugoslavia President Slobodan Milosevic were useless and
unconstructive.
</P>
<P>
"It is always dangerous to talk yourself into a rage and make
false comparison," Schaeuble commented.
</P>
<P>
Germany's government leaders, including Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder and Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, have compared
Milosevic to the Nazis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
