<HEADLINE> Annan to Appoint Mediators on Kosovo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN April 26 (Xinhua)--U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
Monday said in Germany that he would soon appoint two mediators to
seek a peaceful solution to Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the start of his three-day visit to Germany, Annan
said in Berlin that the mediators would go to work as soon as he
finished the necessary consultations.
</P>
<P>
Annan did not mention whom he would choose for the task. U.N.
staff indicated former Austrian Chancellor Franz Vranitzky and
former Swedish Prime Minister Carl Bildt were among the
candidates. Officials said Annan would not appoint mediators that
came from a NATO member country, but prefer one from the west and
another from th former eastern bloc.
</P>
<P>
Annan is unlikely to name the envoys before he arrive in
Moscow, official said. His visit to Russia is scheduled for
Wednesday after meeting with German Chancelor Gerhard Schroeder,
Defence Minister Rudolf Scharping,and Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer.
</P>
<P>
It was the boldest intervention by the United Nations almost
five weeks after the NATO launched air campaigns against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In his talks with German President Roman Herzog, Annan said the
U.N. Security Council should play a stronger role to settle the
Kosovo conflict, and the endeavor must include Russia as well. A
peaceful solution to the region should allow the refugees return
their homeland "quickly and safely", Annan said.
</P>
<P>
It will be a victory of the Europe, the United Nations and the
humankind, if the Kosovar citizens are able to live in peace and
freedom with their civil and political rights fully ensured, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
