<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Refugees in Turkey Reach Over 11,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The number of Kosovo refugees in
Turkey has increased to 11,986 since the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) launched air strikes against Yugoslavia on
March 24.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Interior Ministry said in a statement Monday that
4,712 refugees have entered Turkey from the Tekirdag-Corlu border
gate and 6,592 from the Edirne-Kapikule border gate while 682
embarked in Turkish northwestern port city of Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
At present, 4,451 Kosovo refugees have been sheltered at the
Gaziosmanpasa Refugee Camp in Turkey's northwestern Kirklareli
province.
</P>
<P>
NATO's air strikes against Yugoslav Serb targets began after
the Serb-led government refused to accept a peace agreement to
grant autonomy to the independence-seeking ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians have fled to
neighboring Macedonia and Albania since the air operation, and
still more on the roads.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, with other NATO members, has been asked to take in part
of the refugees before they can return home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
