<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Police Commanders Discuss Anti-Crime Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Police commanders from member
countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
gathered here Monday to begin a meeting on joint measures to
combat criminals in the region, the Vietnam News Agency (VNA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting, the 19th Conference of the ASEAN
Association of Police (ASEANAPOL), is attended by policemen from
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
During the conference hosted by Vietnam's Police Force, the
participants will discuss cooperation programs within the
framework of ASEANAPOL so as to effectively implement part of the
Hanoi Plan of Action and the Hanoi Declaration passed at the Sixth
ASEAN Summit last year.
</P>
<P>
They will focus their discussions on issues relating to
regional drug trafficking, circulation of fraud money, the use of
false passports, economic crimes and transnational swindling.
</P>
<P>
They will also work together to find out measures to boost
mutual assistance in settling criminal issues, exchanging criminal
archive data and statistics and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Public Security Minister Le Minh Huong, his deputy Le
The Tiem and Southeast Asia Regional President of International
Criminal Police Organization Toshinari Kanemoto attended the
opening session of the conference.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Le Minh Huong said he hoped that the
participants would devise objectives and effective measures to
boost cooperation among ASEAN police forces.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia sent a delegation to the conference as observer.
</P>
</TEXT>
