<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Minister Says Racist Groups Difficult to Penetrate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- British Home Secretary Jack Straw
said on Monday the white supremacists blamed for targeting blacks
and Asians recently were hard to penetrate.
</P>
<P>
"We are dealing with a different nature from those, and to some
extent they are more difficult to penetrate," Straw told BBC
Radio.
</P>
<P>
"We are talking about very small numbers of people. There has
been some monitoring of some of these groups but, as we know from
Irish terrorism, with the best will in the world -- even if there
is very extensive monitoring -- they still have a capability to
commit outrages."
</P>
<P>
A nail bomb blasted in Brick Lane in east London on Saturday,
injuring six people. A week earlier, another big explosion ripped
south London, injuring nearly 40 people. The neo-Nazi racist group
Combat 18 has claimed responsibility for both incidents.
</P>
<P>
"We have to show absolute determination to celebrate and
strengthen Britain as a multi-racial society," Straw said.
</P>
<P>
British police were liasing with counter-intelligence
authorities abroad. But they played down press speculation that
the attacks might have links to nail bomb attacks in Paris four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Britain's black and anti-racism leaders have called for a ban
on racist groups and a firm government pledge to introduce tougher
race relations law as quickly as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
