<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workshops Held to Discuss Attracting Capital to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The "1999 Attracting Capital to
Africa Summit" Monday entered its third day, breaking all
participants into 22 workshops, which are expected to last two
days.
</P>
<P>
The Africa Bureau of the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) Monday began a workshop on financial intermediation and the
private sector in Africa to analyze the problems of the private
sector and suggest approaches to help Africa deepen its financial
mediation and attract foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was chaired by Thelma Awori, assistant administer
of UNDP and director of the U.N. agency's Africa Bureau. "Our aim
is to use the event to generate new ideas and concrete proposals
on how to make the African private sector the engine of economic
growth," she said.
</P>
<P>
Five heads of state, four prime ministers and high-level
representatives of some 30 African countries are present at the
five-day summit. The theme for the 1999 summit is "transforming
natural wealth into human capital," which, observers here said,
speaks to one of the most important challenges facing Africa
today.
</P>
<P>
Top U.S. government officials and senior representatives of the
American enterprises also attended the summit to explore
opportunities for two-way trade and investment between Africa and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Doing business with African countries is in the interest of
the United States," U.S. Congresswoman Sheila Jackson Lee told
Xinhua. The United States can do a lot of work in helping women's
businesses and medium-sized enterprises in Africa, she said.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 summit follows on the heals of the U.S.-Africa
Ministerial Meetings held in Washington last month, and these
events are seen as an integral part of the redefinition of the
U.S. ties with Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
