<HEADLINE> Milosevic Ready to Allow Red Cross Work in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic is ready to allow the International Committee of Red
Cross (ICRC) to work in Kosovo, said the ICRC president Cornelio
Sommaruga on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with the French television channel France
2, Sommaruga said: "Milosevic has promised that we could go there
immediately, but I am expecting that be clarified in written
form," said Sommaruga, who has just met with Milosevic in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
"I also need the agreement from NATO and the Kosovo Liberation
Army. I will ask all the parties in the conflict to respect the
symbol of Red Cross," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Red Cross delegates should be able to go around
freely in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC president also said that he discussed the problem of
Kosovo refugees and displaced civilians with Milosevic during
their talks.
</P>
<P>
"He (Milosevic) mentioned his hope to see the return of
refugees," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sommaruga also said that the Red Cross is concerned about the
suffering of all the victims in the war.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his regret that NATO has destroyed three big
bridges across the Danube River, which resulted in the lack of
portable water for 90,000 people in Novi Sad north of Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
