<HEADLINE> Trial of Leading Suspected Militant Starts in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's Higher State Security Court
on Monday began trial of a leading suspected Islamic militant.
</P>
<P>
The defendant, identified as Ahmed Abdel Wahab, was arrested
recently, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported. Abdel Wahab
has been sentenced to death in absentia, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
He was charged with taking part in the murder of a police
major-general, a brigadier and a lieutenant colonel in the
governorate of Qena, 450 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
He was also accused of joining a terrorist group, which seeks
to topple the government by force and assassinates officials and
policemen.
</P>
<P>
Islamic militants began an insurgency in 1992 in an attempt to
overthrow Egypt's secular government and install a strict Islamic
rule. About 1,200 people, mostly police and militants, have died in
the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Egypt usually slaps harsh sentences on suspected militants. In
a major trial in the government's crackdown on Islamic insurgency,
an Egyptian military tribunal sentenced nine militants to death on
April 18 and 11 others received life sentences with hard labor.
</P>
</TEXT>
