<HEADLINE> Kenya's Ruling Party Secures Parliament Majority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's ruling party has secured
its narrow majority in parliament by gaining two seats previously
held by opposition parties, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya African National Union (KANU), which has ruled the
east African country since its independence in 1963, won the two
by-elections in Tigania and Mutomo constituencies in rural eastern
Kenya, although vote- counting was marred by violence in which one
opposition leader was injured.
</P>
<P>
Social Democratic Party leader Charity Kaluki Ngilu suffered
leg, chest and head injuries when a group of young KANU supporters
stoned her car in Mutomo.
</P>
<P>
The results from Saturday's by-elections brought KANU's tally
in the 222- seat parliament to 116 while opposition parties now
command a combined 104 seats. The other two members are the House
Speaker and the country's Attorney General.
</P>
<P>
KANU leaders said the results indicated its continued
popularity despite three years of economic depression.
</P>
<P>
"KANU remains the only party that represents the interest of
all Kenyans and clearly that is why it won," KANU by-elections
organizer Kalonzo Musyoka said. "Opposition parties have not shown
that they can achieve anything for the Kenyan people," he added.
</P>
<P>
But opposition leaders accused local KANU officials of using
money to induce people to vote for the ruling party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
