<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100 GMT, April 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus supports the European Union (EU) decision on
oil embargo against Yugoslavia, said Cyprus Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides Monday.
</P>
<P>
The EU has formally adopted a decision to impose a ban on
deliveries of oil and oil products to Yugoslavia in an attempt to
squeeze fuel supplies to the Serbian armed forces in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
EU called on its 15 members, Cyprus and other candidate
countries to comply with the decision. (BC-Cyprus-EU-Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Kuwaiti Emir Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah Monday invited
Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein to visit his emirate for the
first time since the 1990 Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was conveyed to Abdullah by Kuwaiti Minister of
Justice and Islamic Affairs Ahmad Khaled Al-Kulaib, who is in
Amman to discuss bilateral cooperation in legal and judicial
fields. (BC-Jordan-Kuwait-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinian Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) will be represented at the meeting of the Central Council
of the Palestinian Liberation Organization to discuss the
statehood issue.
</P>
<P>
Hamas spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin Monday announced in
Gaza that he will head a Hamas delegation to the meeting and spell
out Hamas' position on the formation of an independent Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
The Central Council meeting will be held in Gaza on Tuesday to
decide whether Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat should announce an
independent Palestinian state on May 4, when the five-year
transitional period of the Oslo Accords expires. (BC-Israel-Hamas)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will send a letter to
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Monday, expressing his support
for extending "accelerated" final status talks to reach a deal
within a year, local daily Haaretz reported.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said that the letter is due to arrive before
the 124-member Central Council of the Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO) meeting on Tuesday.
(BC-Clinton-Palestine-Letter)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC) has urged
the Palestinian leadership to go ahead with establishing an
independent Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by the PLC in a statement issued after its
meeting held in the West Bank city of Ramallah on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The PLC supports the establishment of an independent
Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital and supports the
Palestinian leadership to begin with all the essential measures
and steps for that, the statement said. (BC-Israel-PLC) 
