<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Urges Church to Help Eradicate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has urged churches across the country to support and complement
government's efforts to eradicate poverty.
</P>
<P>
This was contained in a message read for him at a religious
meeting by the Minister of Justice and Constitutional Affairs
Mayanja Nkangi in eastern Uganda Monday, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said that poverty is one of the major challenges
facing the National Resistance Movement administration.
</P>
<P>
The Church and government must be allies in fighting against
poverty, he added, encouraging churches to urge people to distance
themselves from those attempting to fail the program.
</P>
<P>
The Entandikwa Scheme, a revolving fund for the rural poor,
must be supported and implemented with help from all different
groups.
</P>
<P>
With the continuous efforts by the government to eradicate
poverty, the poverty rate has dropped from 56 percent to 46
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, income distribution is worsening and the gap between
the rich and poor has been widening. Women, who constitute
Uganda's 80 percent of work force in rural areas, only control
five percent of the land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
