<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Deploys More Forces Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon said Monday it
was sending up to 30 more air tanker planes to support the bombing
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Defense Secretary William Cohen is expected to
announce Tuesday the call-up of thousands of U.S. Reserve and
National Guard troops, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The call-up could involve between 20,000 and 33,000 part-time
reserve troops, most of them air crews and support personnel for
the new airplanes, according to U.S. media reports.
</P>
<P>
The new tanker deployment follows an agreement by NATO leaders
at their summit meeting in Washington over the weekend to
intensify bombing against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"All of the leaders left the NATO summit saying they were
determined to intensify the air campaign and this will allow that
to happen," Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"These 30 tankers are really a down payment on a much larger
deployment order that will be coming soon. This is in response to
General Clark's request for approximately 300 planes," Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
About 100 of the 300 aircraft would be tankers, a major
increase in the 137 U.S. air refueling tankers already committed
to the operation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. General Wesley Clark is NATO's supreme military commander.
The new deployment will bring the number of U.S. warplanes in the
operation to nearly 650.
</P>
<P>
"These tankers will immediately help increase the tempo of air
operations, allow us to keep planes on station for longer periods
of time, and increase the number of hours of the day in which
we're actually flying over or near Yugoslavia and Kosovo," Bacon
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
