<HEADLINE> UN Reports Dire Humanitarian Situation in Abkhazia, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Tuesday described the humanitarian situation in
Abkhazia, Georgia as "dire".
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Untied Nations Security Council, Annan
said the failure to reach agreement in January on terms for the
return of refugees and displaced persons to the Gali district and
measures for the economic rehabilitation of Abkhazia, Georgia,
meant that a valuable opportunity was missed to take a major step
forward in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Tensions associated with the upcoming elections in Abkhazia,
Georgia, and economic difficulties, were creating an environment
in which provocations along the lines of separation of forces
might lead to a more general destabilization, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
It was therefore essential that both sides exercise great
restraint in responding to any incidents on the ground, the U.N.
chief said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, two specific actions by the parties
would significantly help improve the situation on the ground: the
full separation of forces from the ceasefire line and the
establishment of a joint investigation mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The report detailed the work of the United Nations Observer
Mission in Georgia, which includes monitoring compliance with the
1994 Moscow ceasefire agreement and progress on the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
