<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Institutes Downgrade German Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN April 27 (Xinhua)--German economy will see a depressed
year 1999 with growth rate lower than expected and the high
jobless rate dropping only slightly, Germany's six leading
economic institutes reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The six institutes are in Berlin, Kiel, Hamburg, Halle, Essen
and Munich.
</P>
<P>
"The cooling of the economy is due largely to foreign economic
factors - the main causes were the crises in Asia, Russia and
Latin America," the institutes said in their spring report.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) growth will be 1.7 per cent
for 1999 and 2.6 per cent in 2000, the institutes said. German GDP
grew by 2.8 per cent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In their autumn report last year, the institutes had predicted
a growth rate of 2.3 per cent for 1999.
</P>
<P>
The German government has lowered its GDP expectation even
further. The Finance Ministry predicts 1999 GDP will grow by just
1.5 per cent instead of 2 per cent as earlier projected.
</P>
<P>
Germany's high unemployment rate will fall only moderately in
the coming years, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 jobless rate of 11.2 per cent (4.3 million unemployed)
will fall to 10.6 per cent in 1999 and 9.9 per cent in 2000, it
said.
</P>
<P>
In eastern Germany, the jobless rate was 18.5 per cent in 1998
and will fall to 17.9 per cent this year and 16.9 per cent in
2000.
</P>
<P>
The institutes said falling unemployment would not mainly be
due to creation of new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment will fall because of the rising number of foreign
guest workers leaving Germany, an aging population, the growing
number of people who put off looking for work to study, more
people retiring before the normal pension age and the creation of
200,000 state-funded jobs for youths.
</P>
<P>
German corporate investment in machinery and equipment is due
to fall in 1999 compared with last year, the report said.
Following a 10 per cent growth rate in 1998, corporate outlays
will grow by 4.5 per cent this year and 4 per cent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
This decline is due to higher wage accords than in previous
years which will average 3 per cent for 1999, while consumer
prices are set to rise by 0.7 per cent this year and 1.5 per cent
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Personal consumption will jump, however, due the rise in gross
wages and tax cuts and other benefits for people with lower
incomes. Real income will grow by 2.5 per cent this year and in
2000 and result in equivalent growth in private consumption.
</P>
<P>
Falling investment in construction will be reversed in the
coming two years, said the report. After last year's 4.3 per cent
decline in the key construction sector, this year's drop will be
just 0.1 per cent, and then will show one per cent growth in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Germany's basic trade balance remains in surplus. Last year
strong exports pushed the German trade surplus up by 13 billion
marks (7.2 billion dollars) to 129 billion marks - the highest
since the 1990 German unification, the report said. Germany's
terms of trade will remain similar for 1999.
</P>
<P>
But a gap in invisible trade pushed the overall German current
accounts balance into deficit of 6 billion marks in 1998, the
institutes said, adding this figure was likely to remain negative
in the coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
