<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Says Liquidity Situation More Relaxed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The liquidity situation in
Thailand was more relaxed during the first quarter of 1999, the
Thai cabinet concluded at a meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a press release from the Government House, the cabinet said
that according to a Bank of Thailand report, the increasing
liquidity has led to declining interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The interbank rate dropped from 2.73 percent in January to 2.25
percent in March while the one-day repurchasing rate has dropped
to 1.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
The increasing liquidity has reflected the ease of monetary and
financial policy since the second half of 1998, the cabinet said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the financial situation tends to be more stable and
people's confidence has returned, it said.
</P>
<P>
As for the liquidity in the business sector, the cabinet
acknowledged the resolutions of a meeting of the Economic
Ministers' Council on Monday that said during the first two months
of 1999, the private sector had more liquidity compared with the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks, whose liquidity has been boosted by the
private recapitalization and government loan package, have lent
more credit to the business community while the outflow of capital
fund has been slowing down.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of capital fund in the private sector from
January to February was as high as 77.2 billion baht (2.08 billion
U.S. dollars) compared with 24.6 billion baht (66.5 million
dollars) in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet expects that the liquidity in the monetary market
will increase due to some key factors, including a
54.4-billion-baht (1.45 billion dollars) loan from Japan, the
easing of conditions of capital risk ratio for commercial banks
and the continuously increasing current account and trade surplus.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
