<HEADLINE> Cisco Systems, UNDP Launch "Net Aid" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Cisco Systems and the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) on Tuesday announced
that they would join forces in an effort to eradicate extreme
poverty in the world's poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
About one-third of the people in developing countries struggle
for survival on incomes of less than 1 U.S. dollar a day. Their
extreme poverty denies them access to such basic needs as safe
drinking water, adequate food and health care.
</P>
<P>
To support its commitment, Cisco Systems, the worldwide leader
in networking for the internet, has pledged its vast resources to
develop a global website which will serve as a powerful source of
information to mobilize the world's people to action.
</P>
<P>
As part of its commitment to alleviating world poverty, Cisco
Systems is creating a website which will be maintained by UNDP.
The site will be solely dedicated to serve as a clearinghouse for
organizations and individuals who want to get involved in the
effort, and have the infrastructure to support more than one
billion hits on the web.
</P>
<P>
in addition to being stocked with information, live interviews,
links and suggestions on how each and every person can help in the
race against poverty, the website will also provide a conduit for
contributions.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet has the power to change the fortunes of
countries,,companies and individuals," said John Chambers,
President and Chief Executive Officer of Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
"Whether it is managing a micro-loan program to purchase
sewing machines for a women's cooperative in Jordan, or accessing
medical expertise for remote clinics in South East Asia, or
educating people on how they can make a difference, the Internet
can play a key role in eliminating extreme poverty," said John.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty eradication must become a central and guiding
objective of all development efforts. Good health, adequate
nutrition, literacy and employment are not favors or acts of
charity to be bestowed on the poor by enlightened leaders. they
are human rights," said James Gustave Speth, Administrator of
UNDP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
