<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Holds Last Rites for Late Communist Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Last rites with full state
honors were held here Tuesday for Nepal's veteran Communist leader
and former Prime Minister Man Mohan Adhikari who died Monday
morning at the age of 79.
</P>
<P>
The late chairman of the Communist Party of Nepal (Unified
Marxist-Leninist, CPN-UML) was the second common citizen in Nepal
to receive such full state honors.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala, ministers and political
party leaders were among those to pay their last tributes to
Adhikari before his body was cremated.
</P>
<P>
A funeral procession through the thoroughfares of Kathmandu was
held before the final rites under the escort of the army.
</P>
<P>
Adhikari fell ill all of a sudden on April 19 while on an
election campaign in the capital. He was his party's prime
ministerial candidate for the parliamentary elections on May 3 and
May 17. He had remained unconscious until his death.
</P>
<P>
The government had declared a three-day national mourning
starting Monday and instructed that the national flag be flown at
half mast at all government buildings and missions abroad in the
period.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday was declared a public holiday. In the past two days,
people from all walks of life lined up to pay their last tributes
to the moderate Communist leader.
</P>
<P>
Adhikari became Nepal's first Communist prime minister on
November 29, 1994, after his party secured the largest number of
seats in mid-term polls. He resigned on September 10, 1995, after
losing a no-confidence motion.
</P>
<P>
On his wish, doctors removed his retinas and successfully
transplanted them on a blind youth on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
