<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Host Int'l Commercial Arbitration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government and the
Asian/ African Legal Consultative Committee (AALCC) have signed an
agreement to establish a regional center for international
commercial arbitration in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Attorney- on behalf of the Nigerian government
and the AALCC.
</P>
<P>
By the agreement, Lagos has joined Kuala Lumpur of Malaysia and
Cairo of Egypt as regional international arbitration centers in
line with the principles of South-South cooperation in trade and
investments.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Ibrahim said that the signing of the agreement
" signifies the final commitment of both parties to achieving the
aim of propagating international commercial arbitration in this
sub-region."
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that as the center begins its actual legal
profession from today (Monday), its existence will assist the
economies of the AALCC developing nations greatly by encouraging
the flow of foreign investments," the Nigerian News Agency Tuesday
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Lagos center will maintain an
international panel of arbitrators and another panel of
conciliators, with each panel made up of eminent jurists, judges
and diplomats drawn from the countries in the Asian-African region
and countries which have close economic links or large investments
in the two regions.
</P>
<P>
The AALCC is an inter-governmental organization, consisting of
45 member states in Africa and Asia with its headquarters in New
Delhi, India.
</P>
<P>
The AALCC has decided to establish three centers within the
Asian- African region. Hence, Kuala Lumpur was selected to serve
Asian countries, Cairo to serve North Africa and Middle East, and
Lagos to serve sub-Saharan Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
