<HEADLINE> Japanese Groups Protest Defense Guidelines Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Demonstrators from Japanese labor
unions and pro-peace groups gathered outside the Diet (parliament)
building Tuesday to protest against the approved three bills for
the implementation of the updated Japan-U.S. defense cooperation
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after mid-day, about 5,000 people attended an emergency
rally in Tokyo's Hibiya district, called by a national liaison
group.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the All Japan Seamen's Union, who took part
in the rally, demanded that the bills, which will enable Japan's
military to render support for U.S. forces in undefined "areas
surrounding Japan," be revoked.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, holding placards and wearing sashes, then
staged a march to the Diet building.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Takako Doi, leader of the opposition Social
Democratic Party (SDP), and other protesters issued an appeal for
joint action to uphold Japan's Constitution, saying the
Constitution's war-renouncing provisions are threatened by the
bills.
</P>
<P>
Also in front of the Diet building, some 300 protesters
belonging to another civic group opposed to the guidelines started
a sit-in in the morning.
</P>
<P>
The approved bills authorize Japan's military to take various
measures in the event of emergencies near Japan, to revise the
Japan-U.S. Acquisition and Cross-Servicing Agreement and to amend
the Self-Defense Forces (SDF) Law.
</P>
<P>
Japan's civic groups and labor unions intensified their
opposition to the bills over the past several days, holding
rallies outside the Diet building and at other locations, calling
for the abolishment of the bills on the ground that they would
draw Japan into war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
