<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macedonian Economic Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Macedonian Economic Minister Zanko
Kado has resigned over the failure of the Western countries to
provide aid to the tiny Balkan nation, whose economy has been
seriously battered by the ongoing Yugoslavia crisis, reports
reaching here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his resignation letter presented Monday to Prime Minister
Lju Bco Georgievski, Kado said he was facing huge difficulties as
the West lacked understanding of the current situation in
Macedonia and failed to give it enough economic aid as promised.
</P>
<P>
Other factors led to Kado's quit included rejections of most of
his proposals by the government and family problems.
</P>
<P>
But the reports did not say whether Georgievski had accepted
Kado's resignation. Georgievski is now in Luxembourg attending
political dialogs between Macedonia and the European Union, the
Council of Europe and the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonian economy has plunged into a crisis since NATO
started the ongoing open-ended bombing of neighboring Yugoslavia,
with which Macedonia has vital economic relations. An exodus of
ethnic Albanian refugees to Macedonia from the Yugoslav province
of Kosovo has made the economic situation even worse.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonian government announced earlier that the conflict
in Yugoslavia is expected to cost the country about 1.5 billion U.
S. dollars in economic loss.
</P>
<P>
At present, unemployment is surging in the country and the
economic growth is slowing down. The latest economic figures
showed that Macedonia's first quarter industrial production fell
30 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Macedonian Foreign Minister Aleksandar Dimitrov said the
country was on the brink of a disaster and urged the West to keep
up their promises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
