<HEADLINE> Beijing's Exports Drop in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's export value dropped 10
percent in the first quarter of this year, even though its total
foreign trade volume rose by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by Beijing Customs, the city's
total foreign trade volume increased by 20.7 percent in the first
quarter of the year, standing at 1.622 billion U.S. dollars. But
exports declined by 10.4 percent to 547 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xuequn, an official with the Beijing Municipal Economic
and Trade Commission, said that both local state-owned and
overseas-funded enterprises witnessed a drop in export value on a
year-on-year basis over the past three months.
</P>
<P>
Zhang attributed Beijing's export decrease to the slow growth
of the world economy and weak market demand.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, devalued currencies have also enhanced the
competitiveness of Southeast Asian states in the world market, and
undermined China's export growth, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
But Zhang is still optimistic that Beijing can achieve its
target of maintaining 2.7 billion dollars in foreign trade this
year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Beijing Municipal Government has adopted
measures to encourage exports, such as increasing cooperation with
overseas commercial entities and developing E-business.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
