<HEADLINE> Anti-Poaching Action: Burning Tibetan-Antelope Skins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese police today burned the
skins of 110 Tibetan antelopes as a special action against rampant
poaching activities in the Hoh Xil Nature Reserve on the Tibet-
Qinghai Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Yang Gangqiang, a police officer with the Qinghai provincial
forestry bureau, said that burning the antelope skins reflects the
government's resolute and unconditional position to prevent the
poaching of this rare animal.
</P>
<P>
"If the confiscated antelope skins were somehow returned to the
market, that would encourage rather than discourage poachers,"
said Yang.
</P>
<P>
The reserve is home to more than 20 rare animal species
including the yak and the Tibetan antelope, and they are all under
state protection.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of April, the police have arrested 17
suspects, and confiscated 11 trucks and jeeps and six guns used
for poaching. 
</P>
</TEXT>
