<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK GCC Chairman Upbeat About HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Peter Sutch, chairman of the
Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce (GCC), expressed here
Tuesday his confidence in Hong Kong's future and advised that Hong
Kong should further promote its international competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong should keep its property prices and wages at a
competitive level and should do business more effectively and
efficiently in order to compete with its regional competitors,
said Sutch at a press conference before the annual general meeting
of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
Sutch, who is retiring as chairman of the chamber and is
leaving Hong Kong for London, expressed his support for the
government's proposals to reform the civil service of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
The government recognizes the importance of an efficient and
cost effective civil service and it is a very important step on
Hong Kong's road to competitiveness, Sutch said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the annual general meeting of the HK GCC, Sutch
noted that the HK SAR has seen dramatic changes since a third of
century ago with the return of Hong Kong to China being only the
most recent dramatic development.
</P>
<P>
"I regard it as a tremendous privilege to have witnessed this
truly dramatic development," Sutch said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has now established itself as one of the world's
major cities for business, for finance and investment; as a key
entry point for international business to China; and as major
travel, tourism, communications and services hub, he said.
</P>
<P>
"As I now prepare to leave Hong Kong for London, I am confident
that with the continued economic opening of the mainland, the
future of the Hong Kong SAR is bright, despite our problems in the
past two years," Sutch said.
</P>
<P>
The last year was an extremely difficult one for the Hong Kong
economy, as the full impact of the east Asian financial crisis hit
home.
</P>
<P>
But like the rest of the community, the chamber responded
quickly to the downturn by cutting costs, increasing the
efficiency of its operations and improving services to members,
Sutch said.
</P>
<P>
Looking to the immediate future, the bad news is that it is
already that the current year is going to be another difficult one
for the Hong Kong SAR business community, he said.
</P>
<P>
The good news is that it should not be as bad as last year, he
continued.
</P>
<P>
Externally, with one or two exceptions, it is apparent that the
regional situation has stabilized, with most of Hong Kong's
regional markets expecting a resumption of positive growth after a
negative 1998.
</P>
<P>
Most importantly, Hong Kong's biggest trading partner, the
inland areas, is looking to further strong growth of some 7
percent.
</P>
<P>
Domestically, there are some signs of improvement, with the
share market doing well and the residential property market
appearing to have stabilized at lower price levels, he said.
</P>
<P>
Inbound travel and tourism numbers improved in the latter half
of last year and have continued to do so in the opening months of
the current year.
</P>
<P>
"Although I am about to leave Hong Kong, I have every
confidence that this vibrant commercial city will recover in the
near-term future," Sutch said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
