<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Constitution Day Marked in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Decorated with pictures and
craft arts supporting Yugoslav's campaign against NATO's bombing,
the embassy of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia held a reception
here today to mark the 7th anniversary of the founding of the
Yugoslav Federal Republic and the formulation of its Constitution.
</P>
<P>
These art works included 2,000 paper cranes made by the
children of Beijing No. 8 Middle School, drawings by Nanjing
University students, and oil paintings depicting scenes in
Yugoslavia after the air strikes by the U.S.-led NATO.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Ambassador Slobodan Unkovic said that this is a
special national day because NATO is still bombing his motherland.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that "we have no choice because we don't have
a second motherland, and we will stick to the end", adding that he
believes Yugoslavia will win the final victory.
</P>
<P>
Unkovic praised China for its support to Yugoslavia on the
Kosovo issue, and said he firmly believes that China will maintain
its just and fair standard in this regard.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Yugoslavia has called on NATO to stop the air
strikes and hold political negotiations with the parties concerned,
presided over by the United Nations, and he stressed that "any
agreements reached will only become effective if the Yugoslav
government accepts them."
</P>
<P>
According to the ambassador, NATO's targets in Yugoslavia,
besides military facilities, have included bridges, hospitals,
factories, and other civilian facilities, and even the Serbian TV
station and a residence of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 days of air strikes have caused economic losses
and many casualties, and have brought about the issue of refugees
and ecological disaster, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador expressed his gratitude to more than 500 guests
from both China and overseas, including over 70 diplomats and 60
ambassadors in Beijing, and he also talked with Wang Yingfan, vice
minister of the Chinese Foreign Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
