<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Succeeds in Massive Transplantation of Alpine Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese botanists have succeeded
in their massive transplantation of alpine plants at the China '99
Kunming International Horticulture Exposition, which is scheduled
to open on May 1 and last till the end of October.
</P>
<P>
"The survival rate of the alpine plants we have migrated to the
Grand Greenhouse of the Expo site has reached more than 99 percent,
" said Liu Peigui, a botanist from the Kunming Institute of Botany
of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Previously there was no record of such massive migration of
alpine plants in the world as it requires strict control of
temperature, humidity, light, ultraviolet ray and alpine wind.
</P>
<P>
The scientists have so far successfully transplanted more than
8,000 alpine plants of more than 400 species to the Alpine Plant
Hall of the Grand Greenhouse, including more than 30 rare species
under the state-class or province-class protection.
</P>
<P>
The massive plant migration project is designed to show the
harmony between man and nature, which is the theme of the
horticultural exposition this year. The other two halls of the
Grand Greenhouse are devoted to tropical plants and flowers.
</P>
<P>
The Alpine Plant Hall is built entirely according to the
ecological environment for alpine plants. It is divided into eight
small areas, which basically represent the typical alpine
vegetation.
</P>
<P>
Home to more than 60 percent of the flora species in China,
Yunnan is known as the kingdom of plants that cover a full
spectrum of climatic zones. Alpine plants mainly grow in
northwestern Yunnan, and more than 5,000 species survive at an
elevation more than 3,000 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
"The scientists spent more than a year deep in the mountainous
areas in the province seeking plants for migration. Most of the
plants, soil and rocks were moved directly from the high altitude
to Grand Greenhouse so as to satisfy the requirements of alpine
plants," said Sun Weibang, a botanist in charge of the migration
project.
</P>
<P>
The botanists have done away with the normal practice of
building interim greenhouses. Instead, they built "natural low
temperature cultivation rooms", known as "bedding in earth". They
then selected the plants that survived, put them into containers
and moved them to the greenhouse for field planting. The migration
of most species was done during their dormant period, thus
ensuring the success of the massive transplantation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
