<HEADLINE> Palestinian, Israeli Officials to Meet Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Senior Palestinian and Israeli
officials are due to meet in the coming days to discuss the
planned closure of three offices of the Orient House, a major
center for Palestinian political activity in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of Israel Radio, the meeting was
requested by the top Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat, who was
trying to persuade the Israeli government not to implement the
closure.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that Israeli Public Security Minister Avigdor
Kahalani will take part in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israel's security cabinet ordered the closure of three offices
of the Palestinian National Authority in the Orient House last
Thursday. And on Monday, Israeli police gave the formal
notification of closure to Faisal Husseini, the top Palestinian
official in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials have said the three offices in the Orient
House have worked for the PNA while the peace agreement signed
between Israel and the PNA ban Palestinian activities in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In response, Husseini has said the Orient House does not
represent the PNA, noting that the compound has been working as a
Palestinian center for years.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
was seeking publicity ahead of the May 17 elections by ordering
the shutdown.
</P>
<P>
Husseini also said that he might appeal the closure order to
the Israeli Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast
war and later annexed it. The Palestinians want to establish a
future capital in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
According to the peace agreements signed by the two sides, the
issue of Jerusalem should be settled in the final status talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
