<HEADLINE> Horti-Expo '99 Host Turns Dumping Line into "Oxygen Bar" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- For more than a decade, Mr. Wang
Yuxing, 72, had to learned to live with a century-old narrow
railway that had been turned into a virtual dumping site and a
stinking river that used to run across this highland city.
</P>
<P>
"The filthy river and the garbage dump along the narrow railway
made it virtually unbearable to live in the vicinity," Mr. Wang
recalled what he felt only two months ago, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
The railway, linking Kunming, capital city of Yunnan Province,
with Hanoi of Viet Nam, was a narrow railway only one meter wide.
The over 600-kilometer-long railway was built and put into service
by France in 1910. It used to be the only outlet of this once
remote and secluded province.
</P>
<P>
The growing city of Kunming gradually besieged the narrow track.
And the rapidly developed transportation, such as air routes,
standard railways and freeways gradually cast the old narrow
railway into the limbo of oblivion.
</P>
<P>
"For a long time, the railway was used to haul coal to the
downtown area once or twice a week only," said Mr. Yang Haiming,
an official with the Kunming Railway Bureau.
</P>
<P>
"When the train passed, the busy traffic near the crossings
would come to a standstill for minutes," Yang said.
</P>
<P>
As time passed, the narrow railway had been left unused,
unattended. People began to dump garbage along the line.
</P>
<P>
"It was simply an eyesore in this spring city," said Mrs. Wan
Xiuying, a 65-year-old retired kindergarten teacher who lives
about 10 minutes walk from the Wujinglu Crossing.
</P>
<P>
But all these have become a memory of the past. The old rail
track was torn away. On the debris appeared a green precinct for
people to do exercises and chatting. All these were done on the
eve of the opening of the '99 International Horticultural
Exposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
