<HEADLINE> Wu Yi: Edge Policy Won't Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- State Councilor Wu Yi warned the
U.S. negotiators today that "the edge policy won't work".
</P>
<P>
Wu, the chief negotiator for over ten years on China's entry
into the late General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade and now the
World Trade Organization (WTO), urged the U.S. to "treasure" the
concession and promise China has made during the bilateral
negotiations on China's accession to WTO.
</P>
<P>
"Some negotiators are reaching out for a yard after taking in
an inch," she said when meeting with a delegation of the Financial
Women's Association of New York (FWA) here today. "They are
demanding too high conditions that are impractical and
unacceptable for China," she said.
</P>
<P>
"China will definitely not agree with this," said Wu.
</P>
<P>
However, Wu also stressed that China is willing to cooperate
with the U.S., adding that "China is the largest developing
country while the U.S. is the largest developed. China is a huge
market for the U.S. and both economies are complementary toward
each other."
</P>
<P>
"If the two countries could cooperate smoothly, that will
contribute greatly to the development of world economy," she said.
</P>
<P>
Wu recalled her recent visit along with Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji to the U.S., saying that the U.S. promised to strongly
support China's entry into the WTO by the end of this year, which
was put in a joint statement signed by Premier Zhu and President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"Even the U.S. side admitted that China has made incredible
concessions," she said.
</P>
<P>
Wu briefed the delegation led by Lenore C. Albom, vice-
president of the Chase Securities Inc., on the financial reforms
in China, adding that she hopes that more financial enterprises
with good credit and reputation would invest in China.  
</P>
