<HEADLINE> Manila to Ensure Safety of Rebel Negotiators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Tuesday that it will ensure the safety of peace negotiators of the
National Democratic Front (NDF) to pave the way for the resumption
of formal peace negotiations with NDF rebels.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said Tuesday afternoon in
the Presidential Palace that a cabinet peace advisory committee he
heads has recommended that provisions of the Joint Agreement on
Safety and Immunity Guarantees earlier forged with NDF be restored
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said Philippine President Joseph Estrada has instructed
government peace negotiators led by Ambassador Howard Dee to
immediately resume peace talks with the NDF following the release
by the rebels of its last government hostage, Sgt. Wivino Demol,
this week.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said the president also stressed that the peace panel
should follow strict guidelines on the resumption of the talks,
which include those requiring that the negotiations be held within
Philippine territory and concluded by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The executive secretary said the government has already
informed the NDF of these guidelines.
</P>
<P>
He said officials involved in the peace process will submit its
recommendation to the president next week on the request of the
NDF to release political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The original list included 50 names drawn up by the government
and two human rights organizations, Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
The president, however, indefinitely suspended peace talks with
the NDF, and put off his announcement on the release of these
detainees following the abduction by NDF rebels of military and
police officers in February.
</P>
<P>
These NDF hostages, including a general, a police inspector and
three military officers, have already been released by the rebels,
signaling the resumption of the formal peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
