<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Weaker on Gold Sales Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar lost
nearly three quarters of a U.S. cent Tuesday, weighed down by
expectations of gold sales by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) and a subsequent slump in the price of the precious metal.
</P>
<P>
Angelo Gangemi, foreign exchange manager of Bankers Trust
Australia, said that after losing ground overnight there was very
little interest in the domestic currency during Tuesday's session.
</P>
<P>
"Basically it's just drifting lower," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished in Sydney at 64.65 U.S. cents,
down from Monday's close of 65.38 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
During the day it traded between 64.62 and 64.94 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Seven nations met in Washington Tuesday and issued
an inconclusive statement on debt relief for developing countries,
saying nothing about the sale of part of the IMF's 103 million
ounces of gold reserves.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has been considering the sale of some of its gold
reserves since September 1996 and the Monday night speculation
resulted in the price of COMEX gold for current delivery tumbling
3.1 U.S. dollars to close at 280.5 U.S. dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
The level of the Australian dollar is strongly dictated by
movements in the gold price as the precious metal is Australia's
second largest export.
</P>
<P>
At the close in Sydney, the Australian dollar was buying 0.6096
euro from 0.6159 euro Monday and 77.32 Japanese yen from 77.74
yen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
