<HEADLINE> China Foresees Severe Floods in Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua)-- The rain belt this year may move
northward as compared with last year, causing big floods in the
upper reaches of the Yangtze River, Huai River and the middle and
lower reaches of the Yellow River in the June-August period.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Wenzhi, vice-minister of water resources made the remarks
here today citing majority opinions of experts.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China is suffering prolonged and lingering drought
in the northern part, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the La Nina phenomenon is expected to
bring about 27-29 typhoons this year in the Pacific, with seven-
nine landing on China, adding that the typhoons will also swamp
China's northern coastline other than the usual southeastern
coastline.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that the Yangtze has enjoyed improvement in its dykes
and levees, basically solving the leakage problem. However, the
Yellow River, whose river bed in the middle and lower section is
higher than the ground, is less well prepared for severe floods.
</P>
<P>
Zhou was speaking at a conference introducing a 14,000-word
book expounding last year's flood situation and a ten-part TV
documentary film of the same topic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
