<HEADLINE> World Bank to Support China's Forest Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is now discussing
with China's State Administration of Forestry on a new project to
help the country protect its forests.
</P>
<P>
The proposed project, called "the Sustainable Forestry
Development Project", is expected to start next year, said an
official from the World Bank Resident Mission in China at a Sino-
Norwegian forestry seminar held here today.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and others plan to invest some 200 million U.S.
dollars in the project, including the World Bank loans of 150
million U.S. dollars, a Global Environment Facility grant of 30
million U.S. dollars, and another grant of 20 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jin, agriculture specialist with the World Bank, said that
a multi-donor identification mission visited China from March 20
to April 3, and the framework and main components of the project
have been worked out.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully," Liu said, "it will be on board later next year."
She added that the preparatory work for the project began last
November.
</P>
<P>
China launched its Forest Protection Program last year in the
wake of severe floods on the Yangtze and Songhua rivers.
</P>
<P>
With the funds provided, this new project will help improve the
protection and management of forests to enhance the sustainable
management of natural resources and environmental development in
China, develop new forestry resources to address China's
increasing wood deficit, and support economic development of rural
households and state enterprises to redress the social and fiscal
impacts of the logging ban.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, the World Bank has financed six forestry projects
in 19 of China's provinces with about 800 million U.S. dollars in
commitments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
