<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preliminary Findings on ROK Plane Crash Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Civil Aviation Administration
of China (CAAC), the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB)
of the U.S, and the Korea Civil Aviation Bureau (KCAB) jointly
issued preliminary findings on the crash of the Korean Airlines
cargo flight 6316 this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The investigation produced no evidence of an explosion before
impact, and no evidence of criminal intent or engine failure.
</P>
<P>
The investigation also indicates that the crew's conversations
with Air Traffic Control (ATC) were routine. The ATC and CVR tape
indicates that all ATC procedures were followed correctly, and
that the flight crew did not request a landing or declare an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
However, the conversations provided by the CVR indicate that
shortly after takeoff the crew experienced a problem in
maneuvering the airplane.
</P>
<P>
But the initial examinations of the crew's comments have not
provided investigators with a sufficient understanding of the
nature of the problem.
</P>
<P>
Radar data indicates that the flight was cleared by ATC
initially to an altitude of 900 meters. The ATC subsequently
cleared the flight to climb to 1,500 meters, and about the time
radio contact was lost, the flight was cleared to climb to 5,700
meters.
</P>
<P>
Korean Air Lines cargo flight 6316 crashed shortly after
takeoff from Shanghai on April 15. The airplane was destroyed and
the two pilots and one flight engineer on board were killed.
</P>
<P>
In addition, five persons on the ground were killed and 37
others injured. Flight 6316 was a regularly scheduled cargo flight
from Shanghai to Seoul.
</P>
<P>
The investigation is being conducted by the CAAC, the NTSB, and
the KCAB. Technical support is being offered by Boeing, Pratt&AMP;
Whitney, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) and Korean Air
(KAL).
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the investigation continues under the
supervision of the CAAC with the full support and cooperation of
the NTSB, KCSB, KAL and component manufacturers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
