<HEADLINE> Former Australian PM Doubts NATO Would Win Ground War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Former Australian Prime Minister
Malcolm Fraser, who returned from Yugoslavia Tuesday, warned of
disaster for NATO if it launched a ground war against Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
Fraser, who traveled to Belgrade to try to obtain the release
of two Australian aid workers accused of spying for NATO, doubted
NATO's ability to win a ground war, which he said could drag
Russia into the conflict.
</P>
<P>
More diplomatic action should have been taken to resolve the
situation in Kosovo, the CARE Australia aid agency chairman told a
press conference in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
"When diplomacy fails and people go to war they really do need
to think through the consequences very, very seriously indeed,"
Fraser said.
</P>
<P>
The former prime minister returned Tuesday morning from
Yugoslavia as Australia's special envoy to Yugoslavia to seek the
release of the Australians detained there.
</P>
<P>
"They (NATO) should have a look at a little history," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Hitler had 20 divisions in Yugoslavia. He was able to occupy
the country but he never suppressed the country," Fraser said.
</P>
<P>
He believed the sending in of NATO ground troops would "make
them (the Yugoslav forces) more determined."
</P>
<P>
Fraser said Russia's attitude would be "highly critical" if
ground forces were used by the NATO alliance.
</P>
<P>
Fraser said his negotiations with Yugoslav officials on the
release of Steve Pratt and Peter Wallace, the two "aid workers" of
his non-governmental aid agency, were productive, but believed it
was best for him to return to Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
