<HEADLINE> Malaysia Gets Loan from Japan for Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will get a yen loan
totaling 6.378 billion yen (50 million U.S. dollars) from Japan to
finance two key projects for its economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's Second Finance Minister Mustapa Mohamed and Japanese
Ambassador to Malaysia Issei Nomura signed the loan assistance
documents here Tuesday, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama
reported.
</P>
<P>
The two projects are the Higher Education Loan Program Part II
and Pahang-Selangor Raw Water Transfer engineering service.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be obtained through Japan's Overseas Economic
Cooperation Fund (OECF).
</P>
<P>
The loan assistance for the first project amounting to 5.285
billion yen (41.43 million dollars) is a scholarship fund for
Malaysian students to go to Japan to study engineering science and
also for the procurement of education equipment and consultancy
services.
</P>
<P>
The loan of 1.093 billion yen (8.57 million dollars) for the
Pahang-Selangor Raw Water Transfer project is to fund the
engineering work for the project.
</P>
<P>
Mustapa said the loan is an extension of a 107.7-billion-yen
(844.31 million dollars) loan to finance five projects in Malaysia
which was agreed upon on March 3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
