<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Strengthen Afforestation Cooperation with Norway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Both Chinese and Norwegian
officials expressed their hopes at a seminar here today that
cooperation in the field of forestry will be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zehui, president of the Chinese Academy of Forestry
Sciences, told the Sino-Norwegian Forestry seminar that Sino-
Norwegian cooperation has great potential in areas such as timber
processing, biodiversity conservation, afforestation, and
scientific research.
</P>
<P>
She noted that China is a forest-deficient country with a
comparatively harsh environment in many regions, and the Chinese
government has always attached great importance to forestry.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the existing planted area in the country
now covers more than 40 million hectares, ranking first in the
world.
</P>
<P>
In the China National Program for Ecological Environment
Improvement worked out at the beginning of this year, there are
plans to cover all the land suitable for afforestation with trees,
raising the forest cover to 26 percent. China's current forest
cover stands at 13.92 percent.
</P>
<P>
"To achieve this, we are willing to work together with
developed countries, including Norway, in addition to relying on
our own efforts," said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
She noted that as a country with developed forestry, Norway has
accumulated a wealth of successful experience and advanced
techniques in such areas as forest operations, biodiversity
conservation, and forestry management.
</P>
<P>
Severe Bergh Johansen, Norway's ambassador to China, also said
that the focus of today's seminar on forestry means a new field
for Sino-Norwegian cooperation will be opened. He noted that in
the world's overall environment and biodiversity, China's forests
play a tremendously important role.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have cooperated in more than 80 environment-
related projects over the past 40-plus years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
