<HEADLINE> New Technology in Cassava Processing Developed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Stored Products
Research Institute has developed technologies for stemming early
deterioration of cassava tubers, Director of the institute,
Ajibola Daramola, said.
</P>
<P>
This Day newspaper Tuesday quoted Daramola as saying recently
the new technology is capable to extending the shelf-lives of
freshly harvested cassava tubers by three months.
</P>
<P>
He explained that after adopting the technology, the tubers are
 available all year round, especially in the production centers of
the crop in the south and central areas in this west African
country.
</P>
<P>
It would also mean availability of more tubers for processing
into products such as garri (the staple food of the Nigerians),
starch and other industrial derivatives, the director added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, essentially, by the technology, freshly
harvested cassava tubers are stored in trenches and saw-dust.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is the leading producer of the crop in the world, which
is an important contributor to national food security and
self-sufficiency for African countries.
</P>
<P>
Cassava production has increased to more than 80 million tons
in the most populous African country from 50 million tons in the
early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Per capita production of the crop in Nigeria was estimated at
about 250 kilograms in the mid-1990s, compared with barely 150
kilograms during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Mopko Bokanga, biochemist and food technologist with the
Ibandan-based International Institute of Tropical Agriculture,
attributed the increase in cassava production mainly to the
development of high-yielding and disease-resistant varieties of
the crop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
