<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Spy Catchers Plan to Spy on E-mail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Australia's intelligence
organization Tuesday revealed plans to go after spies and
terrorists through their computers, financial transactions and tax
records.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Richardson, director-general of the Australian Security
Intelligence Organization (ASIO), said his organization is seeking
changes to its powers which gave it a capability to use
technologies of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
"Access on occasion to taxation information and to financial
transactions can be critical in ASIO's work, especially in the
area of counterespionage and also in the area of politically
motivated violence or terrorism," Richardson told the Australian
Parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"In respect of the latter, there is likely before the end of
the year to be an international convention which will in fact call
for governments to be more aware of the need to access information
relating to financial transaction in the fight against terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Richardson was giving evidence before the parliamentary joint
committee on ASIO which is considering amendments to the ASIO Act.
</P>
<P>
Among the proposed changes, ASIO is seeking the power to access
tax and financial records, break into computers and intercept mail
carried by private contractors and to use electronic tracking
devices.
</P>
<P>
ASIO is currently permitted to intercept telecommunications,
use listening devices and open mail.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said ASIO has not yet broken into computers using
existing technology as that is not permitted under the current
legislation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
