<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's External Trade Value Down in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's re-
exports, domestic exports and imports all registered decreases in
March this year over a year earlier, according to figures released
by the Census and Statistics Department today.
</P>
<P>
The figures show the value of total exports in March was down
10.6 percent to 97.1 billion HK dollars (12.45 billion U.S.
dollars) compared with the same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
The value of re-exports and that of domestic exports
respectively amounted to 85.1 billion HK dollars (10.9 billion U.S.
dollars) and 11.9 billion HK dollars (1.52 billion U.S. dollars),
separately 9.5 percent and 17.5 percent lower than that of March
last year.
</P>
<P>
The value of imports fell by 12.4 percent over a year earlier
to 108.3 billion HK dollars (13.88 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1999, the value of total exports
dropped by nine percent while that of imports fell by 13.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman said that export performance
in 1999 continued to be dampened by the slack import demand in
some of the east Asian economies such as Japan and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The on-going structural shift from re-exports to offshore
trading could have reduced merchandise exports further,
particularly those to the Chinese mainland, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
