<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Scientists Clone 3 Goats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Canadian scientists have cloned
the world's first triplet goats, each of which was developed from
a single adult cell and they share identical DNA, or genetic
makeup, the National Post newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The triplet kids, known as Danny, Clint, and Arnold, were born
in mid-March at a McGill University campus farm. They share a
black spot in the center of their forehead, all have black feet,
the same erect ears, as well as similar head and body shape. Their
cell structures are identical.
</P>
<P>
The three goats are Canada's first cloned livestock using
nuclear transfer, the same procedure used to produce Dolly the
sheep, the world's first cloned animal that was born in 1997 in
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Nexia Biotechnologies Inc. of Montreal, the company that
produced the goats, said the next big scientific step will come
when the company adds special "spider" genes to goat cells from
the triplets to clone more animals, whose milk can then be used
for medical purposes.
</P>
<P>
If the upcoming procedure is successful, the company will begin
breeding thousands of goats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
