<HEADLINE> Cathay Pacific, S. African Airways Plan Joint Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Cathay Pacific Airways and
South African Airways signed a memorandum of understanding here
today, outlining a long-term partnership between the two airlines.
</P>
<P>
Under the document, areas of cooperation include code share
services, frequent flyer programs, and ground handling
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
David Turnbull, deputy chairman and chief executive of the
Cathay Pacific, said at the signing ceremony: "We are extremely
pleased to reach this agreement with South African airways as it
will help us introduce a range of customer benefits for our
services between Hong Kong and Johannesburg."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that the long-term commercial
partnership between the two airlines will do a great deal to help
boost traffic between the two destinations.
</P>
<P>
Coleman Andrews, chief executive officer and president of the
South African Airways, said: "South African Airways is very
pleased to cooperate with Cathay Pacific as we expect Cathay
Pacific will become one of our key partners in our new Asia
strategy."
</P>
<P>
"We will now be able to offer a greatly improved network for
all our customers flying between Asia and Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific commenced flying to Johannesburg in 1991 and
currently operates three flights a week between Johannesburg and
Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
