<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Expected in Addis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a statement on the U.N. envoy's current visit to the Horn of
Africa, Selome said, "Ethiopia, which has always been willing to
work with third parties attempting to mediate a peaceful
resolution to the conflict, welcomes Sahnoun's current efforts."
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun, who is visiting Eritrea and Ethiopia this week,
arrived in Asmara late Saturday night and is expected to further
come here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
His current visit is expected to push for implementation of the
peace plan put forward by the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Both Ethiopia and Eritrea have nominally accepted the OAU
proposals, but no cease-fire has been agreed.
</P>
<P>
Selome said in the statement that "Eritrea must withdraw its
troops from all occupied Ethiopian territories, as required by the
OAU framework agreement."
</P>
<P>
"Specifically, the government in Asmara needs to officially
declare that it will withdraw its troops from all Ethiopian land
and agree to set a short time frame in which the withdrawal will
be implemented," the statement stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Only when the Eritrean authorities agree to these requirements
can a cease-fire take place," she said, adding that "if Eritrea
does not agree to both withdraw its troops and to do so within a
set period of time, a cease-fire will not be possible."
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia accepted the OAU framework agreement in November last
year while Eritrea accepted it in February this year.
</P>
<P>
The 11-month border conflict escalated into fierce fighting in
June 1998 and in February and March this year.
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun's last visit to the Horn of African was made in early
February this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
