<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Exports to Asia Recovering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China's exports to the rest of
Asia are recovering following a first ever negative growth last
year, signs at an on-going trade fair show.
</P>
<P>
Business people from Southeast Asia signed import contracts
worth 630 million U.S. dollars between April 15-26 at the 85th
China Export Commodities Fair, which will close at the end of this
month. The value is 66 percent more than the comparable figure for
the previous fair.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the Republic of Korea and Japan jumped 30 percent
and 13 percent, respectively, according to official statistics,
which indicated that exports to Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan
regions also grew by considerable margins.
</P>
<P>
"These figures show that China's exports to other parts of Asia
are recovering from the effects of the Asian financial crisis," a
trade expert said.
</P>
<P>
That the Asian economy is bottoming out is the major reason
behind the significant growth in Chinese exports to the Asian
market, Gao Mingdou, Secretary of China Council of Machinery and
Electronics Products, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also show that more than 50,000 business
people from other parts of Asia participated in the trade fair by
Monday, up 16.8 percent over the corresponding number for the
previous fair.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the Asian financial crisis, which first broke
out in Thailand in July 1997 and quickly engulfed many other
countries and regions, China last year experienced its first
negative growth in exports to the Asian market in 16 years. Asia
used to be the leading destination of Chinese exports.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China exported 98.3 billion U.S.
dollars worth of goods to the rest of Asia last year, down 9.9
percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
As the financial crisis is widely seen to ease, signs of an
economic recovery in the region have become increasingly apparent
in recent months, allowing Asian business people to be able to
import more Chinese goods.
</P>
<P>
Initial statistics show that turnover at the trade fair totaled
8.89 billion U.S. dollars by Monday, an increase of 12.6 percent
over the comparable figure for the previous fair.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
