<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Not to Send Peacekeeping Force to E.Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States will not send a
peacekeeping force to East Timor because the Indonesian Armed
Forces can maintain stability in the troubled territory, U.S.
Ambassador to Indonesia J. Stapleton Roy said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a dialogue with leaders of various groups in Dili, capital
of East Timor, Roy stressed the Indonesian armed forces'
capability to maintain peace and stability in the former
Portuguese colony, Antara news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Instead of sending a peacekeeping force, the U.S. government
will dispatch a special team to observe the direct balloting in
East Timor," he said before leaving Dili for Denpasar, capital of
Bali province.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the U.S.' stance on the peaceful solution to the
East Timor question, Roy said his government will in principle
accept the decision the East Timorese will make through the
U.N.-sponsored direct balloting.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie Tuesday said in Denpasar that
the direct balloting in East Timor will be held on August 8, and
the government has proposed to the U.N. to invite Australia, the
United States, Japan, the Philippines, Germany and Britain to
observe the event.
</P>
<P>
Roy said if in the long run, the people accept the wide-ranging
autonomy proposed by the Indonesian government, the U.S. will give
its full support.
</P>
<P>
"The differences between the different parties are going to
complicate the process of trying to move forward a credible
process to determine the wishes of the East Timorese people," he
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Roy, who arrived in Dili on Sunday, held dialogues with Bishop
Carlos Belo and East Timor Governor Abilio Jose Osorio Soares,
emphasizing to them the importance of avoiding further violence
and keeping the peace process going.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with a population of some 800,000 and an area of
15,000 square kilometers, had been a Portuguese colony until 1975.
It became an Indonesian province in 1976, but the U.N. never
recognized the move.
</P>
<P>
On January 27, the Indonesian government announced that it was
ready to release East Timor if the alternative to provide wider
autonomy was refused by the people in the region and the
international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
