<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Botanists Furious At Plants Stealing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since 1949, the Chinese government has made great efforts to
protect the country's plant resources through legislation and
intensified customs control, but it has so far failed to
completely wipe out plant theft.
</P>
<P>
"By protecting a species you can protect many kinds of genetic
resources," said Xu Zaifu, another noted botanist in Yunnan. "
Since mankind is still unable to create new genes, the more
existing genes a country preserves, the greater advantage it
enjoys in the global competition in the next century."
</P>
<P>
According to Xu, director of the Xishuangbanna Tropical
Botanical Garden under the Chinese Academy of Sciences, apart from
rare species and ornamental plants, plants with major economic
value or application potential, also need protection.
</P>
<P>
He cited soybean and kiwi fruit as examples. Both plants were
originated in China. But now the largest producers are the United
States and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"Similar things have happened to some medicinal herb native to
China," Xu added.
</P>
<P>
Both Wu and Xu hoped that during the '99 International
Horticultural Exposition scheduled to open in Kunming, capital of
Yunnan, on May 1, botanists from all over the world can discuss
about how to protect more effectively plant resources in
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the two scientists also agreed that in the world today,
it is extremely costly and almost impossible for a country to put
all its plant resources under flawless protection.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of the rapid development of biological
technologies, plant theft no longer necessarily requires
acquisition of seeds," said Wu. "Sometimes a plant can be cloned
with merely a single piece of its leaves."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, the most effective way to protect rare and
valuable plants is to reproduce them by large quantities and to
exploit their economic values fully ahead of others.
</P>
<P>
Xu suggested that the state should increase its financial
support for botanical research so as to enable scientists to find
out the use and application prospects of all known species of
plants in China.
</P>
<P>
"Priority must be given to plants of greatest importance and
highest economic value," said Xu. "Only with a definite objective
in view can we carry out our protection efforts most efficiently."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Botanists Furious At Plants Stealing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Despite the stunning beauty of
that small pot of apricot-color orchid in front of him, Mr.Wu
Zhengyi felt no heart for joy or appreciation. What is on his face
is only sadness and anger.
</P>
<P>
"A native of Yunnan, this flower at one time could be found
nowhere but in China. But now it is not the Chinese who are
studying it carefully or making a good fortune of it," said Wu, an
academician with the Chinese Academy of Sciences who has been
engaged in botanical study for more than 60 years.
</P>
<P>
One of the prettiest members of the lady's slipper orchid
family, the Apricotyellow Paphiopedilum, or "Xinghuangdoulan" in
Chinese, sells for several dozen US dollars a pot on the
international flower market.
</P>
<P>
Wu, now 83, still clearly remembered that this orchid was first
found in the 1950s by Chinese botanists in high mountains in the
western part of Yunnan, but he could never figure out when and how
the flower's seeds fell into foreigners' hands.
</P>
<P>
"But I do know that some foreign scholars and business people
often spent big money purchasing the seeds of China's rare or
precious flowers and trees, and then smuggled them out of the
country," said Wu. "Yunnan has suffered the most from such illegal
activities."
</P>
<P>
Yunnan is reputed as China's "kingdom of plants" as more than
18,000 of the country's 30,000-strong species live in this
southwestern plateau province, many of which have never been found
elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to Wu, who has taken Yunnan as his research base for
more than half a century, Yunnan's plant resources were once
subject to unbridled plunder by foreigners before the founding of
the People's Republic of China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
"At that time, many precious species of flowers in Yunnan,
especially rhododendra, were taken out of China and transplanted
into foreign gardens. This earned China the name 'mother of all
world gardens'," recalled Wu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0163 </DOCNO>
