<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi-Jordanian Oil Pipeline to Start Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The construction of an oil
pipeline between Iraq and Jordan will start soon, an Iraqi weekly
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Economist weekly published on Tuesday quoted an official
source at the Oil Ministry as saying that the ministry and the
Jordanian Energy Ministry are making final preparations for
starting the construction of the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Jordan agreed in 1998 to construct an oil pipeline to
export northern Iraq's oil through Jordan's Red Sea port of Aqaba.
</P>
<P>
The source said that this project will be executed in stages,
beginning with the construction of the pipeline from Jordan's
al-Zarkaa refinery to the Jordanian-Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline construction inside Iraq will be started after
the United Nations sanctions on Iraq were lifted, said the source,
adding that after the pipeline inside Jordan is ready, Iraq will
deliver its crude oil to the border by tankers and pump the oil
into the pipeline inside Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the pipeline from Jordan's al-Zarkaa
refinery to the Iraqi-Jordanian border will cost 300 million
U.S. dollars with the transport capacity of 150,000 barrels per
day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
