<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Lower House Passes Guidelines Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Representatives,
or the lower house of the Diet (parliament), Tuesday adopted three
bills to implement the updated Japan-U.S. defense cooperation
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The move came two days before the week-long visit of Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi to the United States, with the support of
the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), its coalition partner
Liberal Party (LP) and opposition New Komeito.
</P>
<P>
The three bill package authorizes Japan's military to take
various measures in the event of emergencies near Japan, to revise
the Japan-U.S. Acquisition and Cross-Servicing Agreement and to
amend the Self-Defense Forces (SDF) Law.
</P>
<P>
The passage was ensured by a compromise reached Sunday among
the LDP, LP and New Komeito.
</P>
<P>
Under the compromise, the three parties agreed to delete from
the first bill a clause on inspection of foreign ships by the SDF
during emergencies in areas surrounding Japan. They instead agreed
to enact separate legislation on the matter.
</P>
<P>
The three parties also agreed to add to the definition of
emergencies in areas surrounding Japan, the phrase "such
situations which, if remained unchecked, may bring about direct
armed attack against Japan."
</P>
<P>
The original bill only referred to "situations that would have
an important influence on Japan's peace and security."
</P>
<P>
The amended bill also requires prior Diet approval of the SDF's
rear-area logistic support and search and rescue operations.
However, in the event of high-level emergencies, the government
could seek the approval after it has dispatched troops.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's lower house plenary session, members of the LDP,
LP and New Komeito voted for the amended bill, while members of
the main opposition Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ), the Japanese
Communist Party (JCP) and the Social Democratic Party (SDP) voted
against the bill.
</P>
<P>
The other two bills were approved without amendments, supported
by the LDP, LP, New Komeito and DPJ.
</P>
<P>
The SDP and JCP opposed the bills, saying their provisions
could get Japan embroiled in another war.
</P>
<P>
The bills, which were immediately submitted to the House of
Councilors, are certain to become law as the LDP, LP and New
Komeito together hold a comfortable majority there.
</P>
<P>
Apart from some Japanese opposition parties, ordinary Japanese
also expressed their strong opposition to the bills. For the past
several days, people from Japan's civic groups and labor unions
lodged protests at the Diet, and other locations, calling for
discarding the bills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Central Bank Wants Statute Amended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Uganda, the country's
central bank, has proposed a list of amendments to the Financial
Institutions Statute 1993 to create uniformity in the banking
sector.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the amendments is a strong directive to all
commercial banks, local and foreign, to raise their capital base
to two billion shillings (1.4 million U.S. dollars) within the
next eight months, the New Vision paper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Walugembe Musoke, the bank's spokesman, was quoted as saying
Monday that the move is to ensure that there is uniformity in the
banking sector and that the commercial banks are backed by a solid
capital base.
</P>
<P>
Under the Financial Institutions Statute 1993, the minimum
capital requirement for local banks is 357,143 dollars while that
for foreign banks is 714,286 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The draft was sent to Finance Minister Gerald Ssendaula, who is
expected to present it for debate in parliament on a date to be
named.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's move was taken after it closed four
commercial banks within seven months for their mismanagement and
huge inside lending.
</P>
<P>
The recent closure of the Greenland Bank Limited sent another
wave of panic among depositors and the demand for dollars has been
rising sharply, making the shilling depreciate every day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
