<HEADLINE> Rwandan Criminal Court Frees Former Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The criminal court in Kibuye
district, western Rwanda, Monday acquitted a former government
official in a case relating to the 1994 genocide in which he was
allegedly involved.
</P>
<P>
The criminal court ''set free one genocide suspect and also
former sous- prefet (deputy-governor) of Kibuye, (Ignace) Banyaga,
after finding him innocent,'' the Rwanda News Agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution had requested death penalty to the suspect whom
it accused of genocide and crimes against humanity. Banyaga
immediately walked home and joined his family, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources in Kibuye said Banyaga served as personal
 secretary to Clement Kayishema, the former governor of Kibuye,
who is now in the United Nations custody in Arusha, Tanzania, for
involvement in the genocide of thousands of Tutsis who had sought
refuge at the local church, soccer stadium, and the Bisesero
hills.
</P>
<P>
His release surprised many genocide survivors who had accused
him of direct participation in the killings which rocked Kibuye
five years ago, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan prisons are crammed with over 124,000 genocide suspects
waiting for trial. Since the beginning of the trials by the
country's criminal courts in December 1996, up to 1,000 cases have
been handled, with around 150 death sentences.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by a local human rights organization
LIPRODHOR, about 2,000 detainees were released since October 1998.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
