<HEADLINE> Chernobyl Computer Virus Generates Little Fallout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Only 70 computers had been
hit by the so-called Chernobyl virus Monday, much less than
expected, according to the Computer Emergency Response Team (CERT)
at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
Across the world, the Chernobyl virus had affected hundreds of
computers in Singapore, Hong Kong, India, Japan, New Zealand,
Britain, Russia, Malta, Finland and Sweden, CERT said, adding that
the worst damage appeared to be taking place in Singapore, where
at least 150 computers broke down.
</P>
<P>
Among those hit in the United States, 30 to 40 computers used
by Boston College students, said the college spokesman Jack Dunn.
The virus affected only students who did not install antivirus
software distributed by the college last fall.
</P>
<P>
Before Monday, media reports warned that the Chernobyl virus
could wreak havoc around the world.
</P>
<P>
The Chernobyl virus is a variation of the CIH virus, first
reported in the middle of last year. The April CIH virus is called
Chernobyl virus because it's timed to go off on the anniversary of
the Soviet nuclear accident, one of technology's worst disasters
occurred 13 year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
