<HEADLINE> Intel Unveils Fastest Celeron Chip For Lower-Cost PCs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corp., the largest chip-
maker in the world, Monday introduced a Celeron chip running at
466 megahertz as well as Intel 810 chip set for the low end of the
PC market, according to a report from the company.
</P>
<P>
Intel said that the 466 megahertz Celeron is priced at 169 U.S.
dollars in quantities of 1,000. The Intel 810 chip set will range
in price from 25.5 dollars to 32 dollars, depending on the cache
memory, in quantities of 10,000.
</P>
<P>
"We are deadly serious about this segment (low end PC market),"
said Paul Otellini, Executive vice president and general manager
of Intel's architecture business group, at a press briefing. "We
are very very cognizant that this is where the growth is."
</P>
<P>
Intel estimates the chip set could reduce costs of 810-based
Celeron computers by as much as 20 percent, while 466 MHz Celeron-
based computers is available starting at 999 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
That's enough to enable a whole new market for PCs, said
Otellini.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the combinations of a cheaper and faster Celeron
could hurt Intel's rivals. "It is helping to take the wind out of
the sails of AMD and Cyrix," said Kathleen Maher, analyst with
graphics technology watcher Jon Peddie Associates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
