<HEADLINE> Police Investigate Murder of BBC Star </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- British police on Tuesday started
hunting for a hitman who carried out the murder of BBC television
presenter Jill Dando on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Detective Chief Inspector Hamish Campbell told a news
conference at Scotland Yard in London that Dando died after being
shot once in the side of the head with a 9mm semi-automatic
firearm.
</P>
<P>
He said a man police want to question was seen an hour before
the shooting outside Dando's home at 11.30 am in west London.
</P>
<P>
Detectives are still trying to track down a smartly dressed man
carrying a mobile telephone who was seen walking from the scene.
</P>
<P>
Police issued another call for anyone who may have seen the man
in the area following the murder of Dando, 37, who presented
Crimewatch UK and Holiday.
</P>
<P>
Police were also exploring the possibility that Dando may have
been killed by a stalker. She was stalked by a fanatical fan last
year, prompting her to say in an Internet interview that she was
scared for her personal safety.
</P>
<P>
Nick Ross, who co-presented Crimewatch with Ms Dando, said he
could not believe the murder was linked to her television work.
</P>
<P>
He told BBC Two's Newsnight program: "I don't believe there was
any Crimewatch connection with her killing. God alone knows what
the motive is."
</P>
<P>
Dando's murder prompted tributes from the Queen, who was said
to be "shocked and saddened", and Prime Minister Tony Blair, who
was also "deeply shocked".
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old star had been looking forward to marrying a
London doctor later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
