<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Deeply Concerned Over Approval of Military Cooperation Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China is deeply concerned over
the approval of relevant acts of the New Japan-U.S. Defense
Guidelines by the House of Representatives of the Japanese Diet,
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Sun Yuxi said at a regular press
conference today.
</P>
<P>
He said that Japan's adoption of relevant acts, regardless of
the strong concerns of China and other neighboring nations, is
aimed to strengthen the military cooperation between Japan and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
"It runs against the trend of the times, and will bring a new
unstable factor and a negative impact to the security of the
region," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the fact that some U.S. congressmen wrote a
letter to Lee Teng-hui, reaffirming commitment to the Taiwan
Relation Act, the spokesman said that this has gravely violated
the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques and wantonly interfered in
China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
China has expressed strong displeasure and firm opposition to
this, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that U.S. congressmen will, proceeding from the
fundamental interests of the people of both China and the United
States, do more things conducive to the further growth of Sino-U.S.
relations, not the other way round," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
On the Sino-Indian border issue, Sun said China hopes that the
Sino-Indian border issue will be properly settled through friendly
negotiations and on the basis of mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
He said that the related issue is left over from history, and
that both sides have conducted 11 rounds of negotiations on the
issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Maintain Stable Monetary Policies: Dai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Dai Xianglong, governor of
China's central bank, has reiterated that China will keep stable
monetary policies this year to ensure a sustained growth of the
national economy, the Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, the central bank, expected a least
14 percent growth in the broad money (M2) in 1999, Dai was quoted
as saying at a forum Monday.
</P>
<P>
China's money supply has increased steadily in the first
quarter this year with expanding foreign reserves and a stable
exchange rate of RMB yuan, marking a good opening for the
implementation of this year's monetary policies, Dai said in a
speech given at the ongoing '99 China Enterprise Summit.
</P>
<P>
The present active monetary policies have been adopted to
prevent deflation and financial irregularities amidst a sluggish
market, he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March, China's retail prices of commodities had
been falling for 18 months in a row.
</P>
<P>
China has already launched a series of monetary policies that
used financial leverages to stimulate domestic demand in the face
of the rough market situation.
</P>
<P>
To effectively implement the policies, China will attach more
importance to fiscal policies, such as issuance of treasury bonds,
and development of a capital market, which may change more
deposits into corporate capital, according to Dai.
</P>
<P>
Dai has also pledged to reduce the non-performing loans of
commercial banks markedly, develop a deposit insurance system for
local small and medium-sized financial institutions, and finish
regulation of non-bank financial institutions such as investment
and trust companies within two years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
