<HEADLINE> Iraqi Vice President Warns Against New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan has warned the United States against consequences of any
new aggression on Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The vice president warned that Washington would pay high price
if it launched new aggression against Iraq because Iraq was now on
a high degree of vigilance and alert.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan said in an interview with Egyptian newspaper Al-Usbu
that he expected new U.S. aggression against Iraq at any moment,
said the agency.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched four-night of air strikes on Iraq
last December to retaliate what they called Iraq's failure to
fully cooperate with United Nations arms inspectors in charge of
eliminating Iraq's banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan said the U.S. aggression would be existing "as long as
Iraq rejects Washington's resolutions" and called for the lifting
of the U.N. embargo in place since 1990 following Iraq's invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
He denied any form of dialog between Baghdad and Washington,
saying that Iraq has no objection in principle for conducting
serious and constructive dialog on condition that it should be
within the frame of joint interests and non-interference in Iraq's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The vice president further said that whatever flexibility Iraq
would show, what the U.S. was seeking is toppling the national
regime in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He denied reports that Iraq had made good offers to
U.S. companies to work inside Iraq in a bid to press the
U.S. government to change its policy toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan called on Arab countries to exert pressure on the
U.S. government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
