<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Petrochemical Output to Be Raised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf states are expected to
invest substantially in new petrochemical projects, with their
combined production projected to increase from 14 million tons in
1997 to 24 million tons annually over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
"An estimated amount of 13 billion U.S. dollars will be
invested" by Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states in improving
petrochemical output, Tuesday's Gulf News quoted a senior Dubai
government official as saying.
</P>
<P>
In GCC states, namely Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Oman, Qatar,
Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates (UAE), 75 percent of their
petrochemicals production is exported, as against 25 percent by
other producers, said Sultan bin Sulayem, chairman and managing
director of Dubai's Jebel ali Free Zone and Dubai Ports Authority.
</P>
<P>
"Since our industry is export-oriented, our production is set
to increase manifold over the next few years," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the vast oil and gas reserves of GCC states
are the major strength for their new petrochemical projects.
</P>
<P>
"Saudi Arabia has taken the lead and we will maintain our
market share and match growth in global demand by stepping up
production and setting up new facilities," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Understanding the need for a strong petrochemical industry,
the UAE has announced plans to set up four petrochemical plants at
a total investment of about 2.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
With new projects coming up in the region, demand for shipping
and logistics support services will go up, said the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
