<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Could Be Pulled Into Kosovo Conflict: Former Australian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Former Australian prime minister
Malcolm Fraser Tuesday warned that Russia could easily be pulled
into the Kosovo conflict, possibly supplying fuel and arms to the
Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
Fraser, who returned to Melbourne earlier Tuesday morning from
a trip to Yugoslavia as Australia's Special Envoy, said if ground
forces were used by the NATO alliance, Russia's attitude would be
"highly critical."
</P>
<P>
At its recent summit marking its 50th birthday anniversary,
NATO authorized an oil blockade against Yugoslavia, and French
President Jacques Chirac has expressed his concern that the
decision may put NATO in direct conflict with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Fraser made the comment at a press conference in Melbourne
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"I think that if you really want to analyze the situation, to
look further ahead: if they (the Yugoslav forces) are running
short of fuel, would Russia allow them to run out of fuel?"
</P>
<P>
"If they're running short of ammunition, would Russia allow
them to run out of ammunition? "If they need more or better
ground-to-air missiles, you could so easily get a situation where
Russia is just pulled in even if Russia doesn't even want to be
pulled in," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said even though it was true Russia needed Western economic
support, history showed that issues of nationalism and old
alliances always won out over economic realities.
</P>
<P>
Fraser, who is also chairman of the non-governmental aid group
Care Australia, had been to Russia and Yugoslavia to seek the
release of two Care Australia "aid workers" who have been accused
of spying for NATO after being detained by Yugoslav authorities
late last month.
</P>
<P>
Despite his efforts, including talks with senior Yugoslav
officials, the former prime minister failed to persuade Yugoslavia
to release the two Australian "aid workers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Resume Military Drills with Arab States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Jordan will resume joint military
exercises with Arab countries which have been suspended since the
1990 Gulf crisis, the Jordan Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The drills will be conducted with troops from Egypt, Oman, the
United Arab Emirates and Yemen, the paper quoted Jordanian Field
Marshal Abdul Hafez Mira'I Kaabneh as saying.
</P>
<P>
The date for the joint military exercises has not been fixed,
but the war games will be conducted in Jordan and the territories
of the other involved states, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the 1990 Gulf crisis triggered by Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait, the Jordanian armed forces often carried out joint
military maneuvers, especially with member states of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC).
</P>
<P>
However, relations between Jordan and the GCC states, namely
Kuwait, the UAE, Oman, Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Bahrain, soured
during the Gulf crisis because Amman was sympathetic with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Despite the political rifts and a halt to the joint military
exercises, senior military officers from the GCC countries
continued to visit Amman for training courses in Jordan`s military
institutions.
</P>
<P>
King Abdullah Bin Hussein of Jordan went on full gear to mend
Jordan`s relations with the Gulf states after taking throne on
February 8, following his father King Hussein's death.
</P>
<P>
He normalized relations with Kuwait, which were severed during
the Gulf crisis. Kuwaiti Emir Jaber Ahmed Sabah had invited
Abdullah to visit his emirate.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah will be the first Jordanian ruler to visit Kuwait in
more than nine years after the Gulf crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
