<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Century-Old Cactus Survives Transplantation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A cactus that is at least 150
years old has survived a major transplantation more than one year
ago and has recently sent out new sprouts.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for such old tree to survive
transplantation in China, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
The cactus, one of the oldest kept by man in China, is 2.1m
tall, 80cm in the widest part and 30cm in diameter in thickness at
the root. It now grows in the Potted Landscape Garden at the venue
of the '99 International Horticultural Exposition in the
northeastern suburbs of Kunming.
</P>
<P>
The first world expo China has ever hosted, the horticultural
exposition is scheduled to start on May 1 this year in Kunming and
last through October.
</P>
<P>
Looking like a grimacing tiger head or a weird palm-leaf fan,
the cactus formerly belonged to Dai Zhijian, a retired worker in
Fengqing County some 600 kilometers away from Kunming.
</P>
<P>
According to Dai, the cactus was discovered and taken home by
his great-grandmother when she was picking tea in the mountains.
It was then only 50cm in height. It has since been under
meticulous care of the family for five generations or for more
than 150 years.
</P>
<P>
"When my family learned that Kunming would host a horticultural
exposition, we decided to donate the old plant to the garden gala,
" Dai noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the "old age" of the plant made the chance of survival
extremely slim. After one year of waiting, some gardeners at the
exposition venue lost patience and declared the plant's death and
planned to remove it from the garden.
</P>
<P>
But, to their great surprise, fresh sprouts started to burst
out several days ago. Botanists say that this indicates the plant
has survived the transplantation and can become robust again soon.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that nearly 400,000 trees and shrubs of some 3,
000 species have to date been transplanted to the horticultural
exposition venue. Many of them are rare or precious species
donated by residents and units across Yunnan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. F-16 Fighter Crashes in Arizona </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. military officials
confirmed Tuesday that a U.S. Air Force F-16 jet fighter crashed
Monday on a training mission in the state of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
Airman Jill Popst, spokesman of Luke Air Force Base said the
two-seater jet went down in a rugged area at 18:05 (local time)
near the White Tank Mountains, about 30 kilometers northwest of
Phoenix, capital of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
Maj. Kevin Grove, an instructor pilot, and Capt. Stephan Kevin
Kleinheyer, a student pilot, both ejected safely.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth crash of F-16 jet stationed at the base
during the past six months. The last crash occurred on March 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
