<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai To Host Market-Oriented Arts Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai is to stage China's
first international art festival to be run on a commercial basis
between November 1 and December 1, which will feature thirty major
performances by both domestic and foreign drama, dance and music
troupes.
</P>
<P>
Co-supported by the Ministry of Culture and Shanghai Municipal
Government, the Shanghai International Art Festival will feature
foreign symphony orchestras, ballet and opera companies, drama and
musicals with a wide range of Chinese artists also taking part.
</P>
<P>
"The arts festival is to be run as a business enterprise and
the Ministry of Culture and Shanghai Municipal Government will not
invest even a cent," said Zhou Muyao, Vice-Mayor of Shanghai, in a
news release today.
</P>
<P>
Invitations to artistic organizations and the box office
management will be controlled by agents and intermediary companies
who will compete to win the business and be responsible for either
profits or losses, according to Zhou.
</P>
<P>
A three day art exhibition will also be held during the
festival and many cultural agents worldwide will be invited with
the hope of promoting future cultural trade between China and the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Already a number of foreign artistic groups have registered to
attend, including the BBC's Welsh Orchestra and the prestigious
Royal Opera House from the UK along with the French National
Orchestra and the Franz Harary conjuring team from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a one week long African art exhibition will also be
held during the event.
</P>
<P>
As the largest commercial city in China, Shanghai believes it
is mature enough to host a festival on such a scale in terms of
its economic and cultural strength. According to Li Yuanchao,
China's Vice Minister of Culture, Shanghai can hold a one-month
international arts festival annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
