<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Trying to Find out Best Highland Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Agricultural
Research Institute has launched a research program on 696 local
and foreign maize samples aimed at developing a seed type for the
highland areas of eastern and central African countries.
</P>
<P>
Legesse Wolde, coordinator of the national maize research in
the institute, was quoted by Tuesday's Ethiopian Herald as saying
that the research activities are being undertaken in cooperation
with the Mexico- based International Maize and Wheat Research
Institute.
</P>
<P>
Legesse said study teams have been sent to Ambo, Holleta and
Adet research centers to study the maize seeds from central and
south American countries, where they have already started cross
breeding with the local species for a seed type that suit the
conditions in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said the research teams will also study soil types that
produce the highest yields, adding that the research believed to
be successful, will have a great contribution to make in the
achievement of food security.
</P>
<P>
Various countries of east and central Africa including
Ethiopia, Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda, Burundi and Rwanda are among
first to benefit from the research, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
