<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congressmen Urged to Contribute to Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The fact that some U.S.
congressmen wrote to Lee Teng-hui reaffirming commitment to the
Taiwan Relation Act, has gravely violated the three Sino-U.S.
joint communiques and wantonly interfered in China's internal
affairs, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Sun made the remarks when asked to comment on the matter at a
press conference, saying that China has expressed strong
displeasure and firm opposition.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that U.S. congressmen will, proceeding from the
fundamental interest of the people of both China and the United
States, do things conducive to the further growth of Sino-U.S.
relations, not the other way round," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the Taiwan Relation Act, which aims to "
legalize" the U.S. move to interfere in China's internal affairs
by making use of the Taiwan issue, gravely violates the principles
of the Sino-U.S. joint communique on the establishment of
diplomatic relations. The Chinese government and people have
always expressed firm opposition to this.
</P>
<P>
Sun reiterated that the Taiwan issue is an internal affair of
China and no foreign countries are allowed to interfere in it.
</P>
</TEXT>
