<HEADLINE> World Leaders Invited to S. African President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has invited
world leaders and special guests to participate in the swearing-in
of the country' s new president due to be held on June 16, local
daily Sowetan reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Invitations had been sent to 187 leaders for the function,
Thombela Nqcula, spokesman for the Foreign Affairs Department was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Libyan leader Muammar Qaddafi, who could not attend the 1994
inauguration because of the imposition of sanctions against his
government, is likely to attend the ceremony after the Lockbie
Crisis was solved recently.
</P>
<P>
Nqcula said because of security and protocol, the names of the
world leaders likely to attend the event would not be released
ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
The coming presidential inauguration is the second since 1994
which witnessed the first all-race elections in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Thabo Mbeki, currently deputy state president and chairman of
the ruling African National Congress, will be successor of
President Nelson Mandela who has been top leader of South Africa
for five years.
</P>
<P>
The 1994 inauguration attracted at least 65,000 dignitaries,
more than 800 media representatives and 150,000 members of the
public to the Union Buildings in Pretoria, the administrative
capital of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Among the world leaders who attended the function include the
United States' Vice-President Al Gore, Cuban President Fidel
Castro and President of Palestinian State Yasser Arafat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
