<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Ministry Protects Intellectual Property Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Education has
issued a set of regulations to protect the intellectual property
rights of universities.
</P>
<P>
The regulations aim to take full advantage of the talent
available in Chinese universities, and encourage industrialization
of scientific and technical achievements.
</P>
<P>
An Education Ministry official said that the regulations apply
to state-run universities and their affiliated teaching and
research organizations.
</P>
<P>
The intellectual property rights include patents, trade marks,
technical secrets, copyright and other affiliated rights,
universities' log-ins for web-sites, and other intellectual
property rights enjoyed by universities in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
Experts call the promulgation of the regulations a positive
response to the knowledge-based economy hailed by Chinese higher
education circles. Yang Fujia, an academician of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS) said that only under such a protection
system could talented people be encouraged to give full play of
their brainpower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
