<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Local Governments to Determine Pay Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
leave it to the local governments to decide whether to grant pay
increases to workers to help them cope with the rising costs of
living, especially after the oil price hike, Executive Secretary
Ronaldo Zamora said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said a nationally mandated uniform wage hike is unlikely
because of the different needs of workers in every region.
</P>
<P>
"We have to find out the situation in the different regions. We
don't want workers in some regions to get higher wages compared to
workers in other areas," Zamora said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
He said the cost of living, a key factor in determining wage
increases, varies depending on where a worker resides.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Philippine President Joseph Estrada said a wage hike
by May 1 is not likely, but added that the government is now
studying non-wage benefits for workers.
</P>
<P>
Zamora reiterated that the national government has to consider
the plight of non-union members and the jobless as well in any
move to adjust wages.
</P>
<P>
He raised concern that a wage hike now may trigger a rise in
the prices of basic commodities, a situation he said would
adversely affect the jobless and negate the positive effect of pay
increases.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Secretary Bienvinido Laguesma of the Department of
Labor and Employment said that while labor groups are calling for
another round of wage increases to cope with the recent increase
in oil prices, many businesses are not in a position to grant
this.
</P>
<P>
The minimum wage in Metro Manila is 198 pesos (4.95 U.S.
dollars) a day. Labor groups say the sum is no longer enough to
sustain the daily needs of workers and their families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, EU Resume Group Talks for Second Day (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua)-- China and the European Union (EU)
resumed group talks on China's entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO) for a second day here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The group negotiation in the morning focused on the tariffs on
goods trade, and in the afternoon on service trade, according to a
source at the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (
MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
The current round of talks between China and the EU started
here Monday morning, before negotiations between China and the U.S.
on the remaining issues concerning China's accession to the WTO
concluded. The China-EU talks are expected to last for one week.
</P>
<P>
On Monday morning, Long Yongtu, chief representative of
negotiation of the MOFTEC, and Gerard Depayre, deputy director-
general of Directorate General 1 of EC, held one-hour small group
and closed-door talks. They reached consensus on the procedure and
contents of the current round of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Depayre Monday, Long told Xinhua that
China is prepared to make the "utmost efforts" to push forward
negotiations with the EU and will strive to achieve important
progress as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Long said China attaches great importance to its negotiations
with the EU and other members of WTO on China's accession to the
multi-lateral trade body.
</P>
<P>
Long also promised that China will strictly abide by the
fundamental principle of the WTO, namely, the Most Favored Nation
treatment.
</P>
<P>
According to the top Chinese negotiator, the European side has
expressed "firm support" for China's entry into WTO within the
year 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, EU Resume Group Talks for Second Day (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Meanwhile Director-General Renato Ruggiero of WTO said he had
found "encouraging signs" since Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
visited Washington recently and that he believed China could join
the body before November, according to the International Herald
Tribune published on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"I think that since the visit by China's prime minister there
have been many encouraging signs and I believe we can have China
in the WTO by November, when the WTO begins its next trade round
in agriculture, services and electronic commerce," he told the
newspaper's Monday edition.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Chinese and U.S. negotiators concluded the
latest round of talks on the lingering issues regarding China's
accession to the WTO. "The two sides have made pragmatic and
earnest efforts," according to Long.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States conducted the latest round of talks
last Thursday and Friday, which covered topics of the legal terms
for China's entry into WTO, tariffs on industrial goods and
service sector, including finance, insurance and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Both sides said that the last-phase of a negotiation is often
the most difficult, but they have "agreed to continue their
efforts to solve all the remaining issues so as to reach an
agreement at an earlier date," Long said.
</P>
<P>
The time for the next round of negotiations will be discussed
and announced by the two sides later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
