<HEADLINE> New Zealand Tourism Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley Tuesday accepted Murray McCully's resignation from
tourism portfolio.
</P>
<P>
McCully has been criticized these days for his approval of an
unlawful payment of 340,000 NZ dollars (184,000 U.S. dollars) to
former chairman Bryan Mogridge and former deputy chairman Michael
Wall of New Zealand's Tourism Board when they quit the Board last
year after falling out with McCully.
</P>
<P>
According to a media release from the Prime Minister's Office,
McCully will remain Minister for Sport, Fitness and Leisure and
Minister for Accident Rehabilitation and Compensation Insurance.
</P>
<P>
Minister for International Trade Lockwood Smith, who is
currently on a tour of the United Arab Emirates, Iran, Turkey and
Saudi Arabia, has been appointed as Minister of Tourism.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is hugely important to New Zealand. In the year ending
last June tourism was New Zealand's biggest foreign exchange
earner, generating 4.4 billion NZ dollars (2.4 billion U.S.
dollars) in foreign exchange, and supporting approximately 75,000
jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
