<HEADLINE> WB Urges Manila to Adopt Clear Infrastructure Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) has urged the
Philippine government to adopt policy reform measures that would
encourage private sector initiatives in infrastructure
development.
</P>
<P>
The measures, forming part of the Philippine Country Framework
Report of the WB, were discussed recently during a consultation
meeting of the Cabinet-level infrastructure coordination committee
at the National Economic and Development Authority (NEDA).
</P>
<P>
The WB has recommended the inclusion in the country's Medium
term Development Plan (MTDP) for 1999 to 2004 specific provisions
that would spell out how private firms could go about with their
financial investments in public sector infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Philippine government said the WB wants the
government to lay down specific rules that will govern private
sector participation in infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government is part of a multi-sectoral task
force, which is drafting the MTDP for the government.
</P>
<P>
The WB accounts for 2.34 billion U.S. dollars, or 23 percent of
the Overseas Development Assistance (ODA) extended to the country,
which in 1998 amounted to 10.17 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
