<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President on Middle-East Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
said here today that he is "optimistic" about the future of the
Middle-East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I think we will move forward and finalize (the peace process),
" he said. "Whoever will be elected as the prime minister (in the
upcoming Israeli election), he will have no alternative but to
pursue the peace process."
</P>
<P>
On the current situation in the Middle East, he said: "Let's
underline the good things that have happened in the past 20 years.
"
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that the current relations between
Israel and Egypt are "not as good as they should be", but "are
much better than they were in 1976." And in 1977, the Egyptian
President Mohamed Anwar Sadat, who is a "brave man", started the
peace process, he added.
</P>
<P>
At present, he said, "We can talk (with Egyptians) on the
telephone, fly to Egypt, cross the Suez Canal and walk on the
streets of Cairo."
</P>
<P>
He cited the situation along the Israel's borders with Jordan
and Egypt as "quiet", and the border with Palestine as "much
quieter" than it was before.
</P>
<P>
He said that the wars and military conflicts between Israeli
and Arab countries not only led to the loss of life on both sides,
but also caused "bad feelings" that can not be eliminated even in
20 years.
</P>
<P>
On the establishment of the Palestine State, he said that he
hoped all problems would be solved when the talks between Israel
and Palestine resumed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
