Clerides has said he expects to see an initiative on the Cyprus
issue backed by the United Nations, the United States and European
Union (EU) "at the beginning of September at the latest."
</P>
<P>
In a televised press conference Monday night, Clerides
reiterated his readiness to go to the negotiating table without
preconditions, saying the relative U.N. resolutions have laid out
the basis for the talks.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the talks will be convened by U.N
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the G8, comprising the U.S.,
Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Canada and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash was
setting preconditions by demanding the recognition of his
self-styled regime in the north of the island, the withdrawal of
Cyprus' application for EU accession and confederation as the only
viable solution.
</P>
<P>
He said all preconditions set by Denktash are contrary to
relative U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island, but
the peace talks between the two sides have been stalled since
summer in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
