<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Ancient Tree Species Rescued from Extinction (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese horticulturists have
succeeded in multiplying a rare species of tree that dates back to
140 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
Now the population of the tree has grown from the original
seven to 140 and three of them have been moved to the Tree
Exhibition Area of the '99 Kunming International Horticulture
Exposition scheduled to open on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Known as living fossil of the Jurassic period, the species is
called manglietiastrum sinicum law, belonging to the Magnolia
family.
</P>
<P>
According to botanists, it is the only species of the only
genus left from the Jurassic period. The Chinese name "Hua Gai"
comes from its massive crown, which resembles the canopy of the
gorgeous carriage of ancient kings or emperors.
</P>
<P>
With straight and smooth trunk and fragrant flowers, the tree
is of high value for studying ancient plants, for use as timber
and for beautifying the environment.
</P>
<P>
The seven trees of the protospecies are scattered among the
evergreen broadleaf forests in western Yunnan, all standing about
40 meters. Local people call it "satin tree" for its fine texture
and the light green color that shines like satin. It is a valuable
material for making high-grade furniture, carvings and other
artistic works.
</P>
<P>
Geological changes and deteriorating forest ecology have
weakened the propagation ability of the species and the hard nut
of the tree has made it difficult for itself to crack and
germinate. It was observed that there is no new natural sampling
of the tree in a decade, according to botanists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare and Ancient Tree Species Rescued from Extinction (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They collected seeds in September and October every year,
treated them to obtain pure seeds and stored them in wet sand,
sowed the seed in February the following year and moved the young
sprouts to containers for artificial cultivation before being
moved to hillsides for wild cultivation. There are now three
migrant cultivation points in Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
"We have basically mastered the techniques for artificial
breeding of the species," said Zhang Maoqin, a forestry researcher
in Yunnan who is working at the Expo site. "The survival rate has
reached 85 percent to 90 percent."
</P>
<P>
But the seeds used for artificial breeding can only come from
the protospecies and it is very difficult to collect the seeds
from the 40-meter tall trees. "We have to hire local crack tree-
climbers to collect the seeds for us," Zhang added.
</P>
<P>
The artificial breeding of the species is still in the primary
stage, according to Zhang. There is no record of the growth and
development of the species under the natural conditions. It is
already 12 years since artificial breeding began, yet none has
been found flowering or bearing fruit. The flowering age of the
tree remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
Now, Chinese botanists are experimenting with cutting
propagation. Results show that the samplings are strong, but the
survival rate is low. "It is a good beginning," Zhang said. "It
has laid a sound foundation for further exploration." 
</P>
</TEXT>
