<HEADLINE> World Bank Loans Aid North China Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The economy of North China's
Shanxi province has benefited from a total amount of nearly 800
million U.S. dollars in loans from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The 18 projects carried out with World Bank loans have involved
many sectors including highway construction, water diversion works,
environmental protection, and educational and medical development
in mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
The largest loan worth 400 million U.S. dollars in the Yellow
River diversion project will alleviate the province's low level
economic development due to the lack of water resources.
</P>
<P>
And a project involving water and soil conservancy on the Loess
Highlands with loans of 40 million U.S. dollars from the World
Bank which began in 1994 had by the end of 1998 helped cultivate
71,355 hectares of farmland, or 74.1 percent of the planned total,
yielding both economic and ecological returns.
</P>
<P>
The project has so far increased the per capita grain yield
from 374 to 548 kilograms, and the per capita income of rural
residents from 300 to 600 yuan while also boosting the forest
coverage rate in the area from 19 to 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
The second stage of the project, headed by the Ministry of
Water Resources, is now under way. The ministry is to help assist
northwest China's Shaanxi and Gansu provinces, and north China's
Shanxi province, and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region in
dealing with water and soil erosion and land cultivation, which
will benefit 603,000 rural people.
</P>
<P>
Official with the ministry noted that the large project
includes farmland development, vegetation and fruit cultivation,
and small sized water conservancy construction, 12 projects, and
related support services.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's Shanxi anti-poverty project has been ongoing
since August 1995 and has received over 34 million U.S. dollars
from the Bank, helping to provide drinking water for 280,000 rural
people in 330 villages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
