<HEADLINE> O'Neal-Iverson Scoring Race in Final Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Shaquille O'Neal of the Los
Angeles Lakers and Allen Iverson of the Philadelphia 76ers are
entering the final 10 days of the season in a two-man race for the
NBA's scoring title.
</P>
<P>
O'Neal, who led the NBA in scoring in 1994-95 with 29.3 points
per game, has the lead with an average of 26.3 points per game
with five Lakers games to be played.
</P>
<P>
Iverson, who scored 38 points in Philadelphia's 103-86 win
over Orlando Sunday, is currently averaging 26.2 points each game,
only one-tenth of a point behind O'Neal. Philadelphia has six
games remaining.
</P>
<P>
League leadership in more other major statistical categories
is all but assured. Sacramento's Chris Webber leads rebounders
with 13.0 rebounds per game, with Houston's Charles Barkley second
with 12.3 and Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo third with 12.1.
</P>
<P>
Jason Kidd of Phoenix, who posted his sixth triple-double of
the season with 22 points, 14 assists and 10 rebounds Sunday in a
win over Houston, leads the NBA in assists with 10.8 per game,
followed by Washington's Rod Strickland at 10.1.
</P>
<P>
O'Neal, who has twice before led the league in field goal
percentage, looks sure to add a third title as he is currently
shooting 57.7% from the field, well ahead of nearest challenger
Otis Thorpe of Washington at 52.5.
</P>
<P>
Milwaukee's Dell Curry, long one of the NBA's best three-point
shooters, is closing in on his first three-point field goal title
(.476 but is being pushed by Dallas' Hubert Davis (.451).
</P>
<P>
The free throw percentage title is a battle between veterans
Reggie Miller of Indiana (.919) and Hersey Hawkins of Seattle (.
915
</P>
<P>
Kendall Gill of New Jersey is trying to fend off several
challengers in the steals race with 2.57 steals per game, while
Alonzo Mourning of Miami is to be the blocked shots king with 4.02
per game. 
</P>
