<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, nustralian Leaders Discuss E. Timor Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
and Australian Prime Minister John Howard discussed the East Timor
issue in Nusa Dua, Bali, on Tuesday, Antara News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The 90-minutes tete-a-tete talk was followed by a meeting
between the Indonesian head of state and his ministers, and a
meeting between the Australian leader and his ministers, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Habibie was accompanied by Foreign Minister
Ali Alatas, Minister for Defense and Security/Armed Forces
Commander Gen. Wiranto, State Secretary/Minister Akbar Tanjung.
Howard was accompanied by Foreign Minister Alexander Downer and
Defense Minister John Moore.
</P>
<P>
The parallel meetings were not scheduled before.
</P>
<P>
Howard arrived in the Bali's tourist resort on Monday evening
while Habibie's party arrived after the Australian entourage.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the summit signaled not only Australia's
increasing concern about the situation in East Timor, but also
domestic and international pressures for Canberra to help share
the burden amid signs of a possible breakthrough that would
finally settle the East Timor problem.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with a population of some 800,000 and an area of
15,000 square kilometers, had been a Portuguese colony until 1975
and became an Indonesian province in 1976, but the United Nations
never recognized the move.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government announced in January this year that
it is ready to release East Timor if the alternative to provide
wider autonomy is refused by the people in the region and the
international community. A U.N.-supervised vote on the East Timor
future was also decided to be held in July this year.
</P>
<P>
However, violence between pro-integration groups and
anti-integration groups in the territory escalated since the
announcement of the Indonesian government.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, the warring factions signed an agreement to end
hostilities and increased tension in the troubled region.
</P>
<P>
Howard said Monday Australia would be pushing for a peaceful
end to the violence rocking East Timor when it goes into talks
with the Indonesian government.
</P>
<P>
Antara said the two leaders are scheduled to hold a joint press
conference after the parallel meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
