<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's HIV/AIDS Rate Highest in World: World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Infection rate of HIV/AIDS in
Africa, especially in sub-Saharan Africa, is the highest in the
world, according to a World Bank report.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled World Development Indicators 1999, was
issued by the World Bank Monday and it showed that the rampant
spreading of the pandemic has cut life expectancies in the region.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Stiglitz, the bank's senior economist, said in his
keynote speech: "In sub-Saharan Africa ten countries have seen
life expectancies decrease over the past two decades, and in many
of these the rate of HIV/AIDS infection exceeds. In 11 African
countries, HIV infection rates exceed ten percent of the adult
population."
</P>
<P>
A press release from the international financial institution
said adult mortality rates have risen dramatically in some African
countries due to HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The HIV infection rates in the region are among the world's
highest, it added.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, 29 percent of its population aged 15-49 is
infected with the virus, followed by Botswana (25 percent) and
Zambia (19 percent).
</P>
<P>
Africa, which accounts for only ten percent of world's
population, is home to 21 million people suffering from HIV/AIDS,
about 70 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
Some 7,500 new infections happen in the region each day and 87
percent of the world's children infected with the virus are in
sub-Saharan Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
