<HEADLINE> Intel Chief Foresees Leadership Role for HK IT Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- President of Intel Corporation
Craig Barrett said here Tuesday that Hong Kong has opportunities
to make itself a Asia Pacific Internet hub, thus playing a
leadership role in information technology.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an engineering faculty of the Hong Kong University,
Barrett said Hong Kong can build itself into an Asia Pacific
Internet traffic hub, an Internet content hub and an online
financial services hub.
</P>
<P>
These opportunities of Hong Kong come from the city's advantage
in telecommunications infrastructures, bilingual portal access,
productive movie industry and regional financial center status, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, Hong Kong faces challenges that include
insufficient bandwidth, economic slowdown and piracy.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that Hong Kong re-invent its Internet content with
digital technology and bring in innovation in electronic commerce
solutions.
</P>
<P>
Intel, which plans to produce chips running at giga hertz level
by the end of next year, now alone occupies 256-mega hertz
bandwidth while Hong Kong has a total of 243 mega hertz, ranking
third in Asia next to the Republic of Korea and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Barrett also predicted that the volume of Internet economy will
be booming in the next few years and reach 1 trillion U.S. dollars
by the year 2002. He added that the Asia Pacific region will play
an aggressive role in this development.
</P>
<P>
Barrett is now on a five-day tour that will also take him to
Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and Taiwan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
