<HEADLINE> CIH Virus Damages Thousands of Computers in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- At least 7,600 computers were
damaged by the destructive CIH virus in China yesterday, causing
huge economic losses yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
By this morning, more than 100,000 computers across the country
were discovered to be affected to a different extent by the virus,
according to Liu Xu, General Manager of Beijing-based Ruixin
Company, China's biggest anti-virus hi-tech company.
</P>
<P>
"All of our telephones have been busy since yesterday, jammed
by computer users from various sectors and all the provinces," Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
Some three sub-types of CIH virus have been reported so far,
which break out on April 26, June 26 and each 26th, respectively.
The virus may cause damage to both hardware and software.
</P>
<P>
Although many computer users have already had anti-CIH software,
they failed to initiate it, while many others were simply not
equipped with the anti-CIH software, Liu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
