<HEADLINE> Guangdong Nuclear Power Plant Receives ISO "Greencard" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Guangdong Nuclear Power
Joint Operations Co. Ltd. was granted yesterday an ISO14001
authenticated card, to make itself the first nuclear power company
in China to pass the ISO's certification, which is an
international environmental approval body.
</P>
<P>
With a total investment of four billion US dollars, the Sino-
French joint venture operates two one million-kilowatt nuclear
generating units in Daya Bay Nuke in Shenzhen in south China's
Guangdong Province, which is China's first nuclear power plant
using overseas funds for construction.
</P>
<P>
It has taken two years for the plant to meet all the
environmental requirements of the International Standard
Organization (ISO).
</P>
<P>
The ISO report shows that during the five years of operation,
the nuclear plant has used advanced treatment techniques to
control waste discharges. The environment near the plant has
remained as intact as before the operation started in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Daya Bay plant had generated 59.8 billion kwh of
electricity for the power grid of Guangdong and Hong Kong by last
October earning 3.35 billion U.S. dollars and has paid back 51
percent of its loans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
