<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (55) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Following is Part 55 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Can the MSAR continue to participate in any relevant
international organizations and international meetings?
</P>
<P>
Macao is already a member of a number of international
organizations such as the United Nations Industrial Development
Organization, the World Trade Organization, the International
Labor Organization and the International Red Cross, etc.
</P>
<P>
It has frequently participated in international meetings
concerning economic and cultural matters.
</P>
<P>
Under Article 137 of the Basic Law, the MSAR may continue its
membership in the appropriate international organizations and
participate in international meetings.
</P>
<P>
However, its membership and participation shall be conditional
on non-sovereign status. For example, it can not join any
political and military international organizations composed of
sovereign states or participate in any such international meetings
attended by sovereign states.
</P>
<P>
To be specific, the following rules must be observed:
</P>
<P>
The Government of the MSAR may dispatch representatives to
participate, as members of delegations of the People's Republic of
China, in international organizations or conferences in the fields
affecting the Region, organizations or conferences whose
participation is limited to states. Or its representatives may
attend in such other capacity as may be permitted by the Central
People's Government and the international organizations or
conferences concerned. They may express their views, using the
name of Macao, China
</P>
<P>
The appropriate fields here refer to economic, trade, banking,
shipping, communications, tourism cultural, scientific and
technological, sports and a number of others. As for the capacity
as may be permitted by the Central People's Government and the
international organizations or conferences concerned, they will be
decided in the light of the specific conditions.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the International Maritime Organization is an
inter-governmental organization. According to the Constitution of
the organization, it has members and associate members. Any
territory under the jurisdiction of a sovereign state may become
an associate member of the organization provided that the
sovereign state concerned gives its consent to it and that the
territory concerned completes the necessary procedures for
obtaining this status.
</P>
<P>
Macao has now become a separate associate member of the
International Maritime Organization in the name of Macao, with the
consent of both the governments of China and Portugal. The MSAR
may, after its return to China, continue to be an associate member
of that organization in the name of "Macao, China", a capacity
that both the Government of the People's Republic of China and the
International Maritime Organization permit.
</P>
<P>
The MSAR may participate, in the name of "Macao, China", in all
those international organizations and conferences which do not
require statehood for participation.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Macao's membership in those international
organizations which both China and Macao have joined, the Central
People's Government will work out a way to enable the MSAR to
remain in them in an appropriate form in the light of the actual
conditions and needs of the latter.
</P>
<P>
As for Macao's membership in those international organizations
which China has not yet participated in while Macao has already
joined, the Central People's Government will work out a way to
enable the MSAR to remain in them in an appropriate form in the
light of the actual conditions and needs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
