<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Color TV Price War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Two major Chinese color TV
producers have been forced to cut their retail price to compete
with a price reduction made by China's best selling brand of
Changhong.
</P>
<P>
The Changhong Group triggered the price war earlier this month
by chopping 10 percent of its retail price, which means 50 yuan to
800 yuan per unit price reduction on a wide range of TV models.
</P>
<P>
This led to Konka and Skyworth's even sharper adjustment of the
market price. Konka has responded by slashing prices between 100
yuan to 1,500 yuan, while the price of Skyworth TVs was cut by 18
percent. Another large color TV producer TCL is planning a similar
move.
</P>
<P>
This is Changhong's second price cut. The first in 1996 was
made to ensure its safe lead and also kick start the first price
war in the domestic color TV market. At that time, Changhong was
congratulated because it helped expand the market share of
domestic producers by a large margin, compared with a sharp dive
of the sale volumes of imported brands.
</P>
<P>
The second discount strategy has not yet brought any comment
from government officials, but it has been thought to be related
with its expanding inventory.
</P>
<P>
China's color TV manufacturers are turning out more color TV
sets than can be sold right now. Last year, some 32 million color
TV sets were produced.
</P>
<P>
However, there are currently 200 million people in China's
remote areas who do not watch TV, and only 30 percent of the rural
population who have color TV sets. The price cut is good tidings
for many of those who thought they could not afford one.
</P>
<P>
But, for many small-sized color TV producers, the price war
could be another blow like that of 1996 when many were squeezed
out of the market.
</P>
<P>
It has also vexed the national revenue. Last year, the state
coffers recorded a loss of 5 billion yuan in tax revenue, because
of the price cutting competition among domestic color TV producers.
The State Development Planning Commission is now drawing up a new
regulation to focus on discount criteria for the color TV market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
