<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Gv't Approves Draft Privatization Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
approved a draft privatization policy designed to facilitate the
hand-over of state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The draft policy, endorsed by the weekly cabinet meeting on
Monday, also created scope for punishing those violating terms of
agreements after taking over the SOEs, The Daily Star newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"If someone fails to fulfill conditions, the government would
take back the enterprise concerned," Commerce and Industries
Minister Tofail Ahmed was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The government would very soon enact laws in line with the
policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Privatization Board, set up in 1993 to privatize the
loss-making SOEs, drafted the law and submitted it to the
government last year seeking a well-defined and more powerful
authority to quickly do away with the SOEs.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft policy, a 15-member commission would be set up
to replace the existing board, which would comprise six members of
parliament, five ex-officio members, two full-time members, one
chairman and a representative from a professional group to be
nominated by the government. The ex-officio members included the
industries secretary, the commerce secretary and the finance
secretary.
</P>
<P>
The commission, which "will have rule-making power and the
authority to decide independently," would estimate the assets and
liabilities of the SOEs to be privatized, scrutinize tenders and
take necessary measures to hand-over the industrial unites.
</P>
<P>
The proposed commission would have the authority to directly
sell out an enterprise worth up to 250 million taka (5.2 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
At present, the Privatization Board cannot of its own sell or
off-load shares of any enterprise of whatever price without
permission from the prime minister whose office oversees the
board.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the government planned to privatize 51 of
SOEs this year.
</P>
<P>
There are about 300 SOEs in the country, with a total value of
output accounting for about 6 percent of the gross domestic
product and incurring a loss of about 568 million U.S. dollars
every year.
</P>
<P>
The Privatization Board has handed over a total of 17 SOEs to
private entrepreneurs since 1993, with 12 of them up to 1996 and
five in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
