<HEADLINE> Heilongjiang Modernizes State Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province will upgrade 80 percent of its outmoded tractors and
harvesters as well as a great number of auxiliary farm machines in
state farms and land reclamation zones over the next five or six
years.
</P>
<P>
This will cost about 600 million U.S. dollars, said Zhang
Xiangyuan, a senior official of the Heilongjiang Provincial
Administration of State Farms and Land Reclamation.
</P>
<P>
And the upgrading program was kicked off with the recent
arrival in Dalian, a port city of northeast China's Liaoning
Province, of a number of tractors imported from the Fiat-
Newholland company, which have a value of two billion Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The delivery is just part of the administration's massive
international purchasing policy which will partly be covered by
Japanese Government loans to China worth 17 billion Japanese yen,
said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, a large amount of agricultural
equipment will be bought to modernize two of the administration's
large state farms.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang Provincial Administration of State Farms and Land
Reclamation administers 103 farms, the largest number in the
country, which incorporate two million hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
And 85 percent of the work is done by machines and 80 percent
of the grain they produce sold on the open market. Last year, the
administration harvested 17 million tons of grain. 
</P>
