<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Italy Warns of Ecological Disaster After NATO Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Greenpeace Italy said Monday that
NATO's bombings on Yugoslavia would inflict serious and long-term
pollution on the biosphere in the Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
The group said at a meeting here that a great deal of harmful
gases were emitted to the air after Yugoslavia's chemical plants
and oil refineries were hit by NATO bombs, with initial influence
only on surrounding districts, which, however, would contaminate a
considerably large area including the Adriatic Sea in the long run.
</P>
<P>
The all-pervasive gases could lead to disastrous results, even
at very small amounts, and would be quick to spread.
</P>
<P>
The group said that harmful substances, released to the air
after the bombings of the chemical plants and oil refineries,
would go into rains, rivers and sea, polluting drinking water and
sea food, which would lead to an increase of diseases including
cancer.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the escalation of the war in Yugoslavia would
cause many weapon wrecks to fall into the Adriatic Sea, posing a
great danger to navigation in a long time to come.
</P>
<P>
In case of bombings on Yugoslavia's power plants, the
catastrophe would not be restricted to the Adriatic region alone,
but would have a long-term impact on entire Europe, the group
warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
