<HEADLINE> Namibian President Says Africa Is Land of Promise, Opportunity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The world today is increasingly
seeing Africa as "a continent of promise and opportunity" despite
a general sense of pessimism in the United States, visiting
Namibian President Sam Nujoma said here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to 750 representatives from businesses and governments
of both Africa and the United States, Nujoma said, "
Notwithstanding the general sense of Afro-pessimism in this
country and other developed countries, Africa is increasingly
being recognized as a continent of great promise and opportunity.
</P>
<P>
"Our continent and the Southern African region, in particular,
are being described as the next frontier of rapid economic growth,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian president made the statement at the five-day "
Attracting Capital to Africa Summit," which was launched on
Saturday last week.
</P>
<P>
"Individually and collectively, most of the nations on the
continent have laid the groundwork for increased investment and
sustained economic growth," he said. "In most countries, a
peaceful and stable socio-political atmosphere prevails.
</P>
<P>
"We have generous incentives for investors," he said "we are
consistently innovating to enhance our competitiveness in
attracting foreign direct investment."
</P>
<P>
Namibia is among a dozen of the African countries, those in the
Southern African region in particular, which have made great
headway in promoting economic growth and social progress, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Namibia is a country endowed with considerable natural
resources, business potential and a stable socio-political climate,
" he said, appealing for more foreign investment in his country.
</P>
<P>
"By asking you to invest in Namibia, we seek to achieve an
accelerated growth of our economy," he said. "You will be placed
within easy reach of a market of approximately 200 million
consumers."
</P>
<P>
Nujoma gave assurances that his country "is working hard to
position itself as a truly strategic gateway into and from the
Southern African market".
</P>
<P>
The biannual conference is a follow-up to the Africa-U.S.
Ministerial Meeting held in Washington last month. Both
gatherings are seen here as an integral part of the efforts by the
U.S. Government to redefine its relationship with Africa.
</P>
<P>
The first such summit was convened in April 1997 in Virginia in
a move by the United States to better its relations with African
countries after a period of negligence since the end of the Cold
War. 
</P>
