<HEADLINE> WB Finances Municipal Service Project in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will receive 138.60
million U.S. dollars from the International Development Agency
(IDA), the concessional lending arm of the World Bank (WB), for a
municipal service project at a rate of 0.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
A development credit agreement in this regard was signed
between the Bangladeshi government and the World Bank here on
Monday, the Independent daily newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first involvement of the WB in the municipal
project outside Dhaka and Chittagong, according to WB's country
director Frederick T. Temple, who said that this would provide way
to channel fund to small municipalities for their development.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the project, which is to be implemented
during the 1999-2004 period, are to strengthen the institutional
capacity of selected municipalities in city corporations and
improve resource allocation and fiscal discipline, and to
establish a municipal development fund and a municipal support
unit with the Local Government Engineering Department.
</P>
<P>
If implemented, the project will also support government
efforts to reduce urban poverty and improve the environment
condition of urban communities and improve infrastructure, service
delivery system of three towns of Chittagong Hill Tracts and
support post-flood rehabilitation needs of the affected
municipalities. 
</P>
