<HEADLINE> Urgent: China, EU Resume Group Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua)-- China and European Union (EU)
resumed group talks on China's entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO) here Tuesday morning at 10:10.
</P>
<P>
The only group negotiation this morning will focus on the
tariffs of goods trade, Xinhua learned from a reliable source at
the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Five people from EU participated in the group talks, which
started here Monday morning and the current round of talks are
expected to last for one week.
</P>
<P>
On Monday morning, one-hour small group and closed door talks
were first held between Long Yongtu, chief representative of
negotiation of the MOFTEC, and Gerard Depayre, deputy director-
general of Directorate General 1 of EC.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed and reached agreement on the procedure
and contents of the current round of negotiations, Xinhua learned.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Dapayre yesterday, Long told Xinhua that
China is prepared to make utmost efforts to push forward
negotiations with EU and will strive to achieve important progress
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Long said China attaches great importance to its negotiations
with EU and other members of WTO on China's accession to this
world organization.
</P>
<P>
Long also promised that China will strictly abide by the
fundamental principle of the WTO, namely, the Most Favored Nation
treatment.
</P>
<P>
According to the top Chinese negotiator, the European side has
expressed "firm support" for China's entry into WTO within year
1999.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Chinese and U.S. negotiators concluded the
latest round of talks on the lingering issues of China's accession
to the WTO. "The two sides have made pragmatic and earnest efforts,
" according to Long.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States conducted the latest round of talks
last Thursday and Friday, which covered topics of the legal terms
for China's entry into WTO, tariffs on industrial goods and
service sector, including finance, insurance and
telecommunications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
