<HEADLINE> More Japanese Visiting Nanjing Massacre Memorial Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of Japanese
are visiting Nanjing, the capital of east China's Jiangsu Province,
to pay their respects to the victims of the massacre of thousands
of Chinese in December 1937 and to offer their apologies for the
crime committed by Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the year more than 10,000 Japanese
people have attended the Jiangdongmen Memorial Hall, bringing the
total Japanese visitors to the site to 200,000 since the memorial
hall was built in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Since 1986, visiting delegations from the Japan-China Society
have been planting trees annually around the memorial hall to
demonstrate their penitence for the Nanjing Massacre.
</P>
<P>
Japanese visitors also have erected eight monuments in the
memorial hall to urge young generations not to make the same
historical mistakes and to call for friendship between the two
countries and their peoples for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 Japanese students visit the memorial hall every year
to learn about the appalling event.
</P>
<P>
All visitors without exception are shocked at the ferocity of
the Japanese invaders and are indignant at those on Japan's
political right wing who deny the incident took place.
</P>
<P>
Japanese soldiers killed as many as 300,000 unarmed Chinese
soldiers and civilians during the massacre. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
