<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists to Focus on Light Energy for Boosting Crop Yield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have started a
major research program to help better utilize light energy in
raising crop yields, in an effort to meet the food needs of the
country's vast population 30 years from now.
</P>
<P>
This major state sponsored research program, costing a total
of 50 million yuan (6 million U.S. dollars ), ranks first among 14
other major national basic research programs announced recently by
the Ministry of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
China has decided to carry out the basic research programs
over the next five to ten years.
</P>
<P>
Kuang Tingyun, one of the leading scientists involved in the
light energy utilization program and an academic of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS), said more than 100 scientists from CAS
Institute of Botany and others of China's first-rate research
institutions and universities are focusing on a major breakthrough
in the ways in which crops absorb light energy thus increasing the
yield.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Li Liangbi, director of the Institute of Botany's
photosynthetic activity research center, said they plan to seek
ways to raise the light energy utilization rate of rice, wheat and
other major crops from the present 1.5 percent to over 20 percent
in the coming five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that China has put so much investment in
photosynthetic activity research, he added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his belief that the effective utilization of light
energy is of vital importance for raising the per hectare crop
yield and it is believed to be one of the key contents for the
second "green revolution."
</P>
<P>
China's first group of 15 major basic research programs which
involve considerable state funds mainly cover agriculture, energy,
information, resources and environment, population and health as
well as new materials fields, said an official with the Ministry
of Science and Technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
