<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-24 Urges Developed Countries to Open Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Group of 24 developing
countries Monday urged the developed countries to resist
protectionist pressures and further open up their markets.
</P>
<P>
"Ministers expressed concern about the pressure in some
industrialized countries for resorting to protectionism through
various devices," the G-24 said in a communique issued here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Finance ministers of the G-24 held a one-day meeting on the
sidelines of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF)
spring meetings in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"They underscore the necessity of resisting such tendencies and
emphasize the advantage of a further opening up of markets for the
exports of developing countries," said the G-24.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 consists of 24 developing countries, eight each from
Asia, Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The G-24, warning that the world economy remained fragile, said
it was worried about trade protectionism arising out of crisis
that weakened world demand for goods and dealt a blow to
confidence in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
They criticized the high interest rates and tight fiscal
policies in early policy prescriptions from the IMF as it sought
to ease the financial crisis in Asia and beyond.
</P>
<P>
"Ministers noted that some of the prescriptions adopted for
managing the crisis of recent years may have contributed to
adverse affects through unduly restrictive fiscal measures and
high interest rates which have discouraged investment and retarded
the process of recovery," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 also appealed to the IMF to ensure equal access to
developing countries to a new credit line to protect countries
from financial problems in neighboring states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
