<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Vice Minister Arrested on Graft Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Italian police Monday arrested
Treasury Vice Minister Stefano Cusumano on charges of corruption
and Mafia association in connection with the construction of a
hospital in Catania, the second largest city in Sicilia.
</P>
<P>
Cusumano, the first official at the ministerial level arrested
in office in the Italian history, was hospitalized with an attack
of hyper-tension after the arrest. He did not have immunity
because he was not a member of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Sicilian regional councilor for industry, Giuseppe Castiglione,
and eight others were also taken into custody with Cusumano,
accused of tampering with the bidding procedure for the contracts,
corruption and complicity in Mafia association, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
Cusumano and Castiglione, leading figures in Sicilian politics,
are charged with "illegally favoring" the awarding of contracts to
companies linked with the Sicilian Mafia gang of Cosa Nostra.
</P>
<P>
They were suspected of obtaining kickbacks of 120 billion lire
(about 67 million U.S. dollars) from contracts to build the new
hospital in Catania.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to completely get rid of corruption in the
construction area, the Italian National Anti-Mafia Commission
called for the creation of a national task force, made up of
magistrates and law enforcement agents, to closely watch the
awarding of major public contracts.
</P>
<P>
Since Italy launched the anti-craft campaign called "Clean
Hands" in 1992, a number of high-ranking officials were forced to
resign for alleged embezzlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
