<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: China's Private Firms Eyeing International Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A brand new Chinese bicycle is
winning fans all over the world and after a joyful round of
cycling inside a crowded exhibition, Garber Gakobsson, a Swiss
businessman, held his thumb up and told the manufacturer that he
would place an order for one million US dollars worth.
</P>
<P>
The new multi-functional bicycle, with the pleasant name of "Sun
Bird", is produced by the Jinguang Group, a private enterprise in
southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
"This new bicycle, I bet, will sell like hot cakes and I will
import more every year," said Gakobsson, who came here to
participate in the 85th China Export Commodities Fair, the most
important foreign trade event which is held twice a year in
Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time I have attended the Guangzhou fair and
we have signed orders valued at more than 5.6 million US dollars
in less than one week," General Manger Xiao Shuyun told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
It is, in fact, the first time that private Chinese firms have
been able to participate in foreign trade fairs in their own name
and on such a large scale.
</P>
<P>
"With the right to direct foreign trade, we have a much bigger
potential market and greater maneuvering room," Xiao said, adding
his company has developed an environment-friendly model targeted
at overseas buyers.
</P>
<P>
China's numerous private enterprises were not permitted to deal
in foreign trade directly until two groups of 61 firms were
granted the right to engage in imports and exports earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
"By allowing private firms to take part in foreign trade on
their own, China has increased its economic and trade contact with
the world," according to Li Jian, an associate research fellow of
the China International Trade and Economic Cooperation Institute.
</P>
<P>
The private sector has grown by leaps and bounds since China
launched its market economy reforms in the late 1970s. Official
statistics show that China had more than 1.2 million private
businesses by the end of last year, with employees hitting 15
million and a combined output value of 355.9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In recognition of the rising role of the private sector and to
respond to a changing environment, in March China amended its
constitution to boost the private sector's role from that of "
complementary" to being an "important component" of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The participation in direct foreign trade of private firms,
which are generally more market-oriented and efficient than state-
owned enterprises, is expected to boost China's exports, which
have been significantly affected by the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
After years of two digit growth, China's export growth slowed
to 0.5 percent last year, in sharp contrast to 20.9 percent in
1997. In the first quarter of this year, exports declined 7.9
percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials have warned repeatedly that China is facing a
"very tough year for exports".
</P>
<P>
Economists have noted that plunging exports may drag down
economic growth this year.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Premier Zhu Rongji has called for "all possible
means" to increase exports to help stimulate economic growth.
China has set this year's economic growth rate at around seven
percent, down from an actual rate of 7.8 percent last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
