<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Citizens to Be Allowed to Appeal against Government Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese citizens are likely to be
entitled to appeal against government infringement of their
interests and also against "illegal" government documents,
according to a draft law tabled with the top legislature yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The draft law additionally states that citizens, companies and
other organizations may appeal against government documents if
they are considered to have caused an infringement of their
legitimate rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
Li Boyong, vice-chairman of the Law Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), reported the revisions to the ongoing
session of the NPC Standing Committee beginning here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
All government documents can be appealed against except those
signed by the premier, ministers and provincial governors, which,
according to law, are subject to examination by national or local
legislatures, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that this will further open up the government's
activities for public supervision and scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
Government documents, usually with red headers, were considered
as laws when there was not an actual legal system in China. And
even today, they remain powerful, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Legislators said in a previous session that the most common
complaints of the public, such as the essentially illegal
collections of exorbitant fees by local governments, directly
derive from "illegal" and unreasonable government orders and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
Sometimes these law-breaking activities of certain government
employees are following written government orders, they said.
</P>
<P>
The latest draft law also provided that if the complainants are
not satisfied with the results of appeals, they can choose to go
to the court or appeal to higher level of the government, under
the State Council.
</P>
<P>
And the ruling made by the State Council shall be final, the
draft states.
</P>
<P>
Legal experts in Beijing pointed out that such a judicial
review and involvement of the highest level of government shall
help to wipe out the negative influence of departmentalism and
local interests, and serve to safeguard justice.
</P>
<P>
According to an agenda adopted by the Standing Committee here
yesterday, the draft law, which allows greater convenience for the
complainants and heightened efficiency in handling the
administrative appeals, will be voted on at the end of the four
day session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian AIDS Vaccine Effective on Monkeys, Researchers Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Italian researchers announced Monday
that they have further confirmation that the Italian AIDS vaccine
is effective on monkeys.
</P>
<P>
Barbara Ensoli, a researcher at the virology laboratory of the
Italian Health Institute for Higher Studies, reported that the
results of the latest test showed five vaccinated monkeys were not
infected by the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
The laboratory has developed a therapy aimed at immunizing
against the Tat protein which paralyzes cells that normally hinder
the spread of the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
An experiment was carried out on 10 Macaque monkeys, seven of
which were given the vaccine for 50 weeks.
</P>
<P>
Then all 10 were inoculated with a virus called "Shiv," a
mixture of the HIV virus that attacks humans and the SIV virus
that attacks monkeys.
</P>
<P>
After 10 months, the three monkeys which were not vaccinated
all got seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
Of the seven vaccinated monkeys, five showed no sign of the
illness and appeared to have been completely protected, while two
became infected but to a much lesser degree than the three
unvaccinated animals.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine caused no side effects and all seven of the
vaccinated monkeys were said to be in good health.
</P>
<P>
The next step is to carry out the necessary procedures so that
researchers can proceed with testing on humans.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that within one year, such tests can get
underway in Italy and Uganda, the African nation hardest hit by
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Research on animals will continue to fine-tune the methodology
and obtain further information for clinical experimentation.
</P>
<P>
At present, the vaccine has a success rate of 70 percent, but
the researchers want to involve a larger number of animals and are
working for a 100 percent success rate.
</P>
<P>
They also want to try different ways of administering the
vaccine and to target not just the Tat protein, but the gene that
causes its manufacture in the body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
