<HEADLINE> Brazil, Argentina Discuss Trade Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Foreign Minister Luis
Felipe Lampreia and his Argentine counterpart, Guido di Tella,
discussed here Monday trade problems between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
They are trying to estimate the impact of the devaluation of
Brazil's currency, the real, on bilateral trade and seeking
measures to solve the problems.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine government complained that the Brazilian
government did not take measures against the "dumping" of certain
products entering Argentina.
</P>
<P>
It said because of the devaluation and a possible agreement
between Brazil and the Andean Pact, Argentina will cut down
exports by some two billion U.S. dollars in the 1999-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
Brazil argued that Argentina is placing trade barriers to sugar
and rolling steel imports from Brazil, saying it is imposing a
surcharge of 23 percent for sugar and a minimum price of 410
dollars per ton for rolling steel.
</P>
<P>
Argentina is Brazil's second largest trade partner after the
United States. Brazil's imports from Argentina were 8.03 billion
dollars and exports to the country stood at 6.74 billion dollars.
</P>
