<HEADLINE> Chinese Version of Japanese Veteran's Diary Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese version of the
wartime diary by Shiro Azuma, one of the Japanese intruding
soldiers who massacred 300,000 unarmed Chinese soldiers and
civilians in Nanjing in 1937, has been released in east China's
Zhejiang province, where the author surrendered as an invader in
1945.
</P>
<P>
Shiro Azuma was recruited into the Japanese army and sent to
China in 1937. He was engaged in aggressive battles to occupy
major Chinese cities like Tianjin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Xuzhou and
Wuhan, and recorded all this in his diary.
</P>
<P>
He published part of the diary in Japan in 1987, but was later
sued by a former soldier who was described in the diary as a war
criminal.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Higher Court ruled in this man's favor and instructed
that his name should not be made known or any action taken against
him.
</P>
<P>
An appeal by Shiro Azuma, who feels justice should be done, to
a higher court was rejected.
</P>
<P>
However, Shiro Azuma, regardless of being 87 years old in age,
made a special trip here recently to attend the launch of the
Chinese version of his diary.
</P>
<P>
"I know I'm guilty," the man said. "I'll let more and more
people know the real facts of the war, and that's my way to offer
my apology to the Chinese people."
</P>
<P>
Thousands of local residents and students in Hangzhou, in
support of Shiro Azuma, participated in the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"I respect the old man for his courage in admitting the crime
he committed against the Chinese people," said Ding Zijun, a
student at the Hangzhou Institute of Commerce. "Facts are facts."
</P>
<P>
One of Ding's grandfather's brothers was among the victims of
the Nanjing Massacre, Ding said, and that has remained a permanent
hurt for his family.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
