<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-7 Adheres to Growth Strategy of Domestic Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Seven
industrialized countries (G-7) remain committed to a growth
strategy based on strengthening domestic demand and will continue
to support the recovery of emerging market economies, a G-7
statement said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued after a meeting of the G-7 finance
ministers and central bank governors, said the favorable outlook
remains for continuous price stability in the seven countries.
</P>
<P>
"The most important contribution that we can make to improving
the overall global outlook will be to promote sustainable domestic
growth in our own countries, bearing in mind the favorable outlook
for price stability in our countries," said U.S. Treasury
Secretary Robert E. Rubin after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"As far as the U.S. is concerned, prospects are favorable for
another year of strong economic activity," he said. "But it is
very important that Europe and Japan also get on track for solid
and balanced growth."
</P>
<P>
The G-7 finance ministers and central bank governors discussed
the outlook for growth in their countries as well as in the world
economy, global financial systems, and the current situation in
Kosovo and its ramifications for neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the challenges facing each of our economies, we
pledge ourselves to continued efforts to work cooperatively to
strengthen conditions for financial stability and to improve the
economic outlook," said the G-7 statement.
</P>
<P>
Open and competitive international trade markets continued to
be an important underpinning for world growth, prosperity and
stability, the statement stressed.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 countries remained committed to achieving further trade
liberalization and market transparency through the launch of a new
round of multilateral trade negotiations in November.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the meeting reaffirmed that they would
maintain strong cooperation to promote stability of the
international monetary system and exchange rates among major
currencies that were in line with fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
"We reaffirmed our view on the importance of pursuing policies
to promote sound economic fundamentals and more balanced growth
among key economies and thereby help avoid excess volatility and
significant misalignments of exchange rates of major economies,"
Rubin said. "We will continue to monitor developments in exchange
markets and cooperate as appropriate."
</P>
<P>
On the debts of poor countries, Rubin said the G-7 reiterated
the importance of strengthening the initiative of the Heavily
Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) and reviewed the proposals made by
a number of G-7 countries with a view to reaching consensus by the
Cologne summit in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
