<HEADLINE> Worldwide Toy Sales Up in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide toy sales,
consisting traditional-type toys and computer games, totaled 67.8
billion U.S. dollars in 1998, according to a report released
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a 2.7 percent increase from 1997 sales of
66 billion dollars, said the International Council of Toy
Industries (ICTI) which consists toy trade associations from 21
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the worldwide toy industry worked
together to release industry sales on a global basis, according to
the ICTI.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide traditional-type toy sales excluding computer games
in 1998 totaled 53.5 billion dollars, a slight decrease from 1997
sales of 54.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The average toy expenditure per child was 34.63 dollars
worldwide in 1998, the ICTI said. Sales via the Internet totaled
10 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to Toy Manufacturers of America, total U.S. toy
industry sales in 1998 were 27.2 billion dollars. Of these,
traditional toys totaled 21 billion dollars, while computer games
sales reached 6.2 billion dollars, up 20 percent over a year
before. 
</P>
</TEXT>
