<HEADLINE> Shanghai Invests More Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
industrial and commercial city, is now working out an overall plan
for more enterprises to invest abroad.
</P>
<P>
According to a source with the municipal government, the new
plan will encourage local businesses to establish research
institutes as well as trade and manufacturing subsidiaries in
other countries.
</P>
<P>
This is a further step by Shanghai to open its economy wider
and compete more directly in the international market, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has already opened 511 businesses in more than 70
foreign countries and regions since its first overseas company was
set up in Hong Kong in 1981.
</P>
<P>
These enterprises, involving total investments of 368 million U.
S. dollars, mainly center on electrical appliances, textiles,
pharmaceuticals, as well as tourism, transportation, finance and
other sectors. About one-third of the enterprises are now
profitable.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Foreign Economic Cooperation Group, the city's largest
overseas enterprise, has been doing business in more than 110
countries and regions, and is setting up its African, Southeastern,
South American and Middle East headquarters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
