<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Reports Negative Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China's largest city of Shanghai
has registered a population decline for seven consecutive years,
with a 1998 drop of 1.8 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show an annual birth rate of 5.3 per
thousand and a death rate of 7.1 per thousand for last year. That
means a natural decrease of 23,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attribute the downward trend to a successful
family planning policy that has brought the birth rate down by
nearly 3 per thousand over the past decade. About 95 percent of
married couples in the city have chosen to have only one child
each.
</P>
<P>
Experts also point to an upward death rate trend due to an
aging population. Some 20 percent of the local residents are now
above the age 60.
</P>
<P>
The decline in population has had its impact shown in many
sectors of the city, resulting in a shortage of old folks' homes,
and a surplus of kindergartens and primary schools.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that the local population will keep on dropping
in the years to come.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
