<HEADLINE> Measures Called for Protection of Pine Trees in Mt. Huangshan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Experts from the Chinese Research
Institute of Forestry and the State Forestry Administration have
called for measures to combat nematodiasis, a plant disease
endangering pines in the Huangshan Mountain in east China's Anhui
Province.
</P>
<P>
Huangshan, a scenic spot and tourism destination, is well-known
for its pine trees, grotesque stones, hot springs, and unusual
clouds.
</P>
<P>
Pine trees near and around the scenic spot and the 176,000 ha
of forestry in Huangshan City are being threatened by the disease
which was first carried into China by long-horned beetle in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 67,000 ha of pine forestry in Jiangsu, Zhejiang,
Guangdong, Anhui and Shandong provinces have been damaged by the
disease.
</P>
<P>
According to an official with the Anhui provincial forestry
department, the province will implement a protection project
starting this year and use satellite remote-control techniques to
monitor the disease.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is sponsored by the State and the provincial
government, will cost 59.99 million yuan and be completed within
five years.
</P>
<P>
A 100 kilometer long and four kilometer wide control zone will
be established around the Huangshan Mountain in a bid to prevent
the spread of the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roof of World Used to be Damp Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have found a
range of fossils during a comprehensive scientific survey on the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, known as the "Roof of the World", according
to a book published here recently.
</P>
<P>
"The fossils are leaves of a broadleaf tree from a subtropical
zone," said Wu Yuhu, an associate research fellow, in a book
entitled "On-the-spot Report of Scientific Exploration at Kunlun
Mountains."
</P>
<P>
"This shows that Qinghai-Tibet Plateau was 1,000 or 2,000
meters above sea level at that time. And its climate is similar to
that of Kunming, capital of southwest China's Yunnan Province," Wu
said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the scientists have discovered a karst cave, which
has stalactites and stalagmites which are common in subtropical
areas in south China.
</P>
<P>
The discovery shows that the arid and frigid Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau was a damp subtropical area. It is identical with local
folklore that tells how the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau used to be a
vast sea.
</P>
<P>
Two other researcher who took part in the exploration said
these fossils are vital to the study of the age and geographical
changes on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
