<HEADLINE> More Poor People in Ningxia Move to Better-Off Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- More than 33,700 poor rural
residents are expected to be resettled in newly built villages in
the Hongsibao Irrigated Area, in northwest China's Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region, this year.
</P>
<P>
Built on a former artillery shooting range the area covers 50,
000 ha of land along the Yellow River, the second longest in China.
It is believed to be the largest poverty relief project in China.
</P>
<P>
Under the regional poverty relief plan, one million people
living in Xihaigu, one of the country's poorest area, will move to
an fertile area and develop 133,000 hectares of arable land along
the Yellow River with the use of special water pumping equipment.
</P>
<P>
The project, started in 1995, has already built three pumping
stations along the 23 km long canal. Over 318 million yuan of
investment, including 33 million U.S. dollars in loans from Kuwait,
have been used in building 3,400 houses, opening up 1,800 ha of
farmland and planting 189,000 trees in and around Hongsibao.
</P>
<P>
Over 16,000 households with a population of 8,700 in Xihaigu
have moved into new resettlement villages and an estimated 5,300
ha of arable land will be opened up this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Trade Surplus Improves for 19th Straight Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's trade surplus in March
of this year grew for the 19th straight month by 17.5 billion baht
(510 million U.S. dollars), according to the Customs Department of
the Thai government.
</P>
<P>
The value of exports in March declined year-on-year in baht
terms by 1.4 percent to 177.9 billion baht. The dollar value
declined by 1.2 percent to 4.77 billion U.S. dollars, the
department was quoted Tuesday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
The baht value of imports in March declined year-on-year by 7.4
percent to 160.4 billion baht. The dollar value rose by 6.8
percent to 4.26 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country's top 10 exports items were computers, electrical
appliances, electrical circuit, garments, rubber and products,
plastics and related products, rice, gems and jewelry, vehicles
and parts, and seafood, the department said.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 import items were electrical machinery, electrical
circuit boards and components, chemicals, machinery, base metals,
crude oil, computers and components, iron and steel, textiles, and
scientific equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
