<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Philippines' Landslide Rises to 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from the Mt.
Diwalwal landslide of southern Philippines rose to 16 as rescuers
dug up two more bodies over the weekend, the Manila Post reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, more than one hundred families have
fled the gold-rush site of Mt. Diwalwal in Compostela Valley for
fear of more landslides.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted sources of the Civil Defense Office as saying
that two more bodies were recovered in sitio Balite, one of the
four villages hit by landslides last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the landslides had killed 14 people and
injured another 11.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Defense Office also said another landslide occurred
in a village in Mawab town, Compostela Valley, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Authorities had attributed the landslides to the deadly
combination of soil erosion and the heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's environment officials said they had
warned the residents of the area as early as September last year
about possible landslides due to heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
Despite the warning, the residents, mostly small-scale miners
trying their luck in the famous gold-rush mountain, opted to stay,
thus exposing themselves to danger.
</P>
<P>
The national weather bureau had reported on Friday that the
rains in Compostela Valley would continue until mid-1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
