<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Government Agrees to Merger of German, Italian Telecom Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Italian government has initially
agreed to Telecom Italia's (TI) plan to merge with German Telecom
"Deutsche Telekom (DT)", announced Minister of Communications
Salvatore Cardinale on Monday, calling the consolidation "a great
opportunity" for the development of the Italian telecommunication
industry.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the sidelines of a telecommunication
conference, Cardinale said that "the merger plan represents a
great opportunity which we can't afford to miss, and it would lead
to our company becoming, along with DT, the second largest in the
world telecommunication sector" after Japan's NTT.
</P>
<P>
Last week in London, DT and TI unveiled their plan for a merger
which would primarily create a 170-billion-U.S.-dollar behemoth
with more than 90 million customers worldwide and 23 million
mobile phone subscribers.
</P>
<P>
Both TI chief Franco Bernabe and DT head Ron Sommer stressed
that it would be a "merger of equals," with both having an equal
say in the running of the proposed company, and Bernabe pledged
that the Italian government would be convinced by the business
plan.
</P>
<P>
However, the Italian government expressed serious doubts,
centering on the proposal that DT hold a 56-percent stocks in the
new company, while the German government still holds a 72-percent
stake in DT and has been unwilling to set out a clear time-table
for the completion of the national telegraphic industry's
privatization process.
</P>
<P>
At Monday's conference Cardinale stressed that "there must be
management equality between DT and TI, and we must make sure that
the Germans are not at the helm."
</P>
<P>
He said that "it seems that these problems have been resolved,
because there is a five-year equal partnership proviso."
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the "gradual privatization" of DT was
acceptable if it is carried out in a clear and transparent way.
</P>
<P>
A group of DT representatives arrived in Rome today to begin
the work on hammering out better details of the merger with their
TI counterparts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
