<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide PC Sales Grow in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Strong consumer demand and
rebounding Asian-Pacific markets resulted in a 19 percent growth
of worldwide PC sales in the first quarter this year, according to
a report released Monday by U.S. market research firm
International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
Worldwide sales rose to 24.5 million units, the IDC said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another U.S. market research firm, Dataquest,
estimated the global PC sales growth in the first quarter at 17.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
The IDC and Dataquest pegged U.S. computer sales growth at 21
and 24 percent, respectively. Much of the growth was driven by
strong consumer desktop demand across not just the low-cost
segment but the full range of price points, the IDC said.
</P>
<P>
In Western Europe, where the United Kingdom, France and Germany
experienced strong consumer demand, there was a continued surge in
PC sales. Markets in Asia-Pacific also continued to reverse the
negative growth pattern that marked much of 1998. Elsewhere, the
IDC said, economic woes in Russia were offset by strong demand in
the Middle East and Canadian markets.
</P>
<P>
Vendor performance worldwide continued to be healthy even in a
time of fierce price wars and limited revenue growth, the IDC said.
</P>
<P>
The fight for market share remained very intense among the top
five U.S. PC vendors -- Compaq, Dell, Gateway, Hewlett-Packard and
IBM. Despite lackluster financial performance, Compaq, with
worldwide shipments totaling 3.53 million units, retained its top
position in unit sales in the first quarter, although its growth
was much lower than the first quarter last year. According to
Dataquest, Compaq's PC sales in the United States only grew 6.9
percent, leading to a drop in its market share to 15.7 percent
from 17.8 percent in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Use Freon-Free Substance As Refrigerant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- All car air conditioners produced
by China will use the freon-free substance R134a as refrigerant
starting on January 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the measures adopted by China to help save the
threatened ozone layer, which protects the environment from direct
exposure to ultraviolet sun rays.
</P>
<P>
At present, annual domestic demand for R134a has reached 2,000
tons and the figure is expected to climb to 5,000 tons by the end
of the century.
</P>
<P>
Many countries have banned the use of freon as it is suspected
of playing a role in the destruction of the atmosphere's ozone
layer.
</P>
<P>
China will totally phase out the use of freon by the year 2005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Prevention On Curriculum at Shanghai's Universities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- AIDS prevention has become a
required course at 15 colleges and universities in China's largest
city of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
This is a positive response to college students' lack of
knowledge about the fatal disease, according to an official with
the Shanghai Municipal Educational Commission.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the commission and the Shanghai Medical
University found that most college students in the city do not
have adequate basic knowledge about AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The commission has therefore issued a regulation, Basic
Requirements for Education on Prevention of AIDS and Other
Venereal Diseases, requiring all Shanghai-based universities and
colleges to add the prevention of sexually orientated diseases
such as venereal diseases and especially AIDS to their curricula.
</P>
<P>
Students will be encouraged to read books, attend lectures and
seminars, and watch videos about the diseases.
</P>
<P>
Young people are especially vulnerable to venereal diseases,
the official said, so great efforts must be made to enhance health
education among them.
</P>
<P>
Medical experts have warned that Shanghai could be on the verge
of a rapid growth of HIV/AIDS cases if public awareness of
preventative measures is not given priority.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last November, the city, which has some 13
million residents, had 183 people registered as infected by HIV,
or the AIDS virus, according to an earlier report. But experts
estimated that the actual figure might be higher and will possibly
reach 16,000 next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
