<HEADLINE> China Urges Increase of Resources Flow to Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- China on Monday urged the
international community, particularly the developed countries, to
spare no efforts in reversing the downward trend of resources flow
to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"Such efforts will bring benefits not only to developing
countries, but also to developed countries themselves," said Jin
Liqun, China's vice finance minister, at the 61st Ministerial
Meeting of G-24 here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Looking at the global economic trend from a broader perspective,
it was obvious that the gap between the developing countries and
developed countries has been widening rather than narrowing, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Promoting financial resources transfer to developing countries
would exert a profound overall impact on eliminating the adverse
effect of the financial crisis, narrowing the gap between the
North and South, stimulating global market demand and promoting
world economic growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
China supported the enhanced efforts on the initiative of
Heavily Indebted Poor Countries where debt reduction would be more
closely linked to poverty alleviation, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In order for debt reduction to be effective, the critical
issue is to provide additional financial resources for development
assistance," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
