<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Treasury Bill Yields Fall to 2-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippines' Treasury bill yields
declined Monday to their lowest in two years after the Central
Bank cut its closely watched interest rates anew to spur bank
lending, the Manila Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At an auction of government securities, the average rate for
the bellwether 91-day bill, which banks use to set loan rates,
fell to 10.202 percent from 10.361 percent a week ago.
</P>
<P>
It was the 17th week of declines for the benchmark bill, which
at the end of 1998 was yielding 13.475 percent.
</P>
<P>
The yield on 182-day treasury bill fell to 10.587 percent from
10.672 percent, while the rate for 364-day bills fell to 10.875
percent from 10.927 percent.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Central Bank cut its overnight borrowing rate
for the 11th time this year to 10.375 percent from 10.875 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank has been seeking to lower borrowing costs to
boost company spending and pull the economy out of recession.
</P>
</TEXT>
