<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Developing Compulsory Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Seventeen of the Tibet Autonomous
Region's 75 counties have now adopted the six-year mandatory
education program.
</P>
<P>
Between them these seventeen counties have a combined
population of 678,100, accounting for 27.9 percent of Tibet's
population.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, four of them have begun to eliminate
illiteracy among youngsters and middle-aged people under 45 years
old. The population of the four counties is 236,700, accounting
for 9.79 percent of Tibet's population.
</P>
<P>
A local education official says that Tibet has a comprehensive
education system from elementary and secondary education to higher
education and professional and adult education.
</P>
<P>
Its elementary education system has improved in the past seven
years and now gives 81.3 percent of the school-aged children a
chance to attend school, a 34.3 percent increase from 1991.
</P>
<P>
Tibet now has a total of 4,365 schools at all levels and plans
to introduce the six-year mandatory education policy in all its
counties. When it is completed by next year, over 85 percent of
all school-age children in Tibet will have the opportunity to
attend school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
