<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archipelago City To Build Sea-Crossing Bridges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The offshore island city of
Zhoushan in east China's Zhejiang Province is preparing to build a
total of six sea-crossing bridges, in a bid to build a peninsula
by linking several local islands with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the project will cost 5.8 billion yuan and
will involve a total of 32 kilometers of highways, including more
than 10 kilometers of the combined span (length) of the six
bridges.
</P>
<P>
The project is planned to be carried out in three phases and is
expected to be completed in the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The island city hopes that the central government will jointly
back the project.
</P>
<P>
Zhoushan, which is composed of more than 1,500 islands, enjoys
abundant ocean resources and is renowned as one of the country's
major fishing grounds.
</P>
<P>
The city has 183 kilometers of coastline with water depth
beyond 10 meters. The handling capacity of local ports exceeded 15
million tons last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
