<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old-folks Home for Returned Overseas Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- North China's Tianjin
Municipality has recently opened an old-folks home for senior
returned overseas Chinese and their relatives, the first one of
its kind among the over 80 old-folks homes in the city.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the Tianjin Municipal Office of Overseas Chinese
Affairs said that it means to provide the senior citizens with
more psychological care, which will please their family members
abroad, and at the same time improve in an indirect way the city's
investment environment.
</P>
<P>
The homes are of the same standard as a middle-class hotel and
boast a reading room, a drawing room, a gymnasium and a Karaoke
hall.
</P>
<P>
Among the over 1,700 overseas Chinese who returned to China in
the 1950s and 1960s, about 80 percent have retired. Moreover, the
number of relatives for the 20,000 overseas Chinese since the year
1978 has accounted for nearly 300,000. 
</P>
