<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Gov't Vows to Promote New Ties With Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government Monday said
that it is determined to promote "a new relationship with Africa."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to some 750 representatives from the business and
political realms in both Africa and the United States, William
Daley, U.S. secretary of commerce, said, "President (Bill) Clinton
has asked all of us in his administration to make an all-out
commitment to promote a new relationship with Africa."
</P>
<P>
Daley has been to Africa five times in his two years as
secretary of commerce, including accompanying President Clinton on
his visit to Africa in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"What I have seen through all this is the positive impact that
market-based reforms have for the African economies. I have seen
the challenges governments face when they seek to open up to the
world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I have also seen that there are tremendous opportunities for
American businesses," he said. "Last year, U.S. exports to Africa
grew a very good 8 percent. This is in sharp contrast to our
overall trade picture with the rest of the world."
</P>
<P>
"But what concerns me is that in the last decade, two-way trade
between America and Africa has lagged considerably behind trade
with other regions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our export assistance centers here at home also are focusing
more on Africa," he said, citing a move to hold "a virtual trade
mission to Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
"What we are increasing is video conferencing capabilities," he
said. "So smaller companies can go into our offices in America,
and make links to the world without expensive travel."
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to reduce the number of costly, time-consuming
trips a U.S. executive must take before a deal can be signed," he
said. "Additionally, we are continuing our efforts to bring
American companies to Africa."
</P>
<P>
But "African leaders need to know you are interested in their
growth as well as your own corporate expansion," he said. "They
seek partners -- partners for the long haul -- partners who can
help integrate Africa more fully into the world economy."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of commerce made the remarks at the five-day
"Attracting Capital to Africa Summit," which began here last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 22 workshops were held Monday to explore
opportunities for the two-way trade and investment between Africa
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The current gathering follows on the heels of the U.S.-Africa
Ministerial Meetings held in Washington last month. Both events
are seen as an integral part of the redefinition of the U.S.
relationship with Africa.
</P>
<P>
Many people credit the United States' re-awakening to Africa
with President Clinton's announcement of his Partnership with
Africa in 1997, followed by his historic visit to Africa in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, African countries have long been haunted by unfair
trade terms, heavy debt burdens and poor living standard of
African people. The U.S. government needs to work hard to rid
Africa of AIDS disease, better the investment environment and
fully integrate into the world economy, rather than promoting its
value systems into the continent, observers here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0367 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of Commerce on Attracting Capital to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. government official
Monday said that private companies in the United States "look for
two main things" to make final decision on where to invest and
where not to.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to some 750 representatives from both the political
and business world of Africa and the United States, U.S. Secretary
of Commerce William Daley said, "First, they want to know if a
country has its economic house in order."
</P>
<P>
"Companies look at the fundamentals of fiscal policies. They
look for progress in privatizing and cutting trade barriers. They
look at infrastructure -- at roads, phone service and reliable
power," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is another sensitive issue -- intellectual property," he
said. "When companies like Pfizer spend half a billion dollars to
develop a drug, they want to know their intellectual property will
be protected."
</P>
<P>
The second thing businesses look at is the political situation.
Even if all the economics are favorable, it will take political
stability also," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The increased fighting in so many countries -- the waste of
such great human and resource potential -- sends the picture to
the world of the old Africa, not the new Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Business people don't want to buy into the old Africa. This
negative news is a turn off. We see stories about fighting and
discord, and enthusiasm for Africa lessens, to be frank with you,"
he said. "These are, of course, real issues that must be
addressed."
</P>
<P>
Daley made the remarks at the five-day Attracting Capital to
Africa Summit, which began here last Saturday, drawing African
leaders and American firms into discussion on how to improve trade
and investment between Africa and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, Thelma Awori, assistant administrator of the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and director of the
UNDP's Africa Bureau, told Xinhua that the U.N. agency "needs to
change the image that Americans have of Africa."
</P>
<P>
Apart from reported conflicts and poverty on the continent,
Africa also has a lot of success stories, such as Botswana, Ghana,
Mauritius and Namibia, which all enjoy political stability and
economic progress.
</P>
<P>
The summit was held as an integral part of the efforts by the
U.S. government to redefine its relationship with Africa, which is
rich in natural and human resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0368 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Faces Opportunities for Economic Growth: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- African countries, after colonial
rule, conflicts and civil strife, are facing enormous
opportunities for economic growth and social progress, Prime
Minister Navinchandra Ramgoolam of Mauritius said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The African countries are free from colonial rule and facing
full opportunities" for economic development and social progress,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the remarks at the five-day Attracting
Capital to Africa Summit, which began here last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Conflicts and civil strife are gaving way to economic
cooperation," he said. "Africa is opening its doors (to the
outside world) because Africa cannot go alone."
</P>
<P>
In introducing Ramgoolam, Thelma Awori, assistant administrator
of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and director of
the UNDP's Africa Bureau, said that the prime minister "is the
precursor of a development philosophy currently known as `economic
diplomacy.'"
</P>
<P>
"Under his leadership, Mauritius has been at the forefront of
promoting African economic cooperation and integration," she said.
"The success story that is Mauritius is now almost legendary in
Africa and serves to encourage those who continue to struggle for
the acceleration of economic development in the rest of the
continent," she said.
</P>
<P>
Without gold and diamond, Mauritius began its economic debut on
the basis of developing the sugar industry. Nowadays, the country,
with a population of some 1 million, has helped Madagascar create
45,000 jobs in two years in the textile industry and is now
supporting Mozambique to develop export processing zones.
</P>
<P>
"The bold efforts of Prime Minister Ramgoolam have been
instrumental in delivering these achievements and in creating an
economy that is now one of the strongest in Africa," she said,
citing such measures as visionary leadership, strong and
constructive partnership between government, the private sector
and trade unions, and strategic investment in human capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
