<HEADLINE> Van Hooijdonk Still for Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Nottingham Forest football club
player Pierre Van Hooijdonk has been on the transfer list since
last August, when he effectively went on strike, but up to now
nobody wants to buy him.
</P>
<P>
The recalcitrant Dutch forward has now outlasted two Forest
managers and seen the club return to the premier league and get
relegated since he went on the transfer list.
</P>
<P>
Yet he seems no nearer to leaving himself.
</P>
<P>
"To be honest, there's been very little interest in him" said a
spokesman for Forest, who are bottom of the premier league and
were relegated at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"(Manager) Ron Atkinson had no offers during his time and there
were not very many during Dave Bassett's."
</P>
<P>
Van Hooijdonk, who joined Forest in 1997 and has three years
left to run on his contract, was transfer-listed by former manager
Bassett before the start of the season with a price tag of 8.0
million pounds (12.92 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the situation remained "pretty much as we
were. He's still on the transfer list."
</P>
<P>
He went on strike after the 1998 World Cup in protest because
he said, rightly as it turned out, that promoted Forest had failed
to buy enough quality players to survive in the top flight.
</P>
<P>
The Dutchman, accompanied by security guards, returned to
Forest in October to an uneasy reception.
</P>
<P>
"I would have left him to rot in Holland," Bassett was quoted
as saying in one newspaper. "He's really coming back to be sold
because, as far as I am concerned, he has no long-term future here.
"
</P>
<P>
Bassett was fired in January, Atkinson, his replacement,
announced on Saturday that he was quitting at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
Van Hooijdonk remains up for sale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
