<HEADLINE>   Richards Named as Premiership Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Sheffield Wednesday football club
chairman Dave Richards has been appointed as the new chairman of
the FA Premier League.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the Hillsborough club has held the role in an
acting capacity since Sir John Quinton quit the post last month.
</P>
<P>
Sir John and Premier League chief executive Peter Leaver both
resigned in a row over lucrative contracts which were awarded to
two former BSkyB executives without the prior knowledge of the
chairmen of the 20 top-flight clubs.
</P>
<P>
Richards' appointment was confirmed following an unanimous vote
at a meeting of the Premier League clubs' chairmen in London on
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Sir John Quinton and Leaver believed they had the authority to
offer the deals signed by Sam Chisholm and David Chance but the
Premier club chairmen refused to back them.
</P>
<P>
The controversy began last November when Chisholm and Chance
were signed up to help the Premier League renegotiate their next
TV rights deal, which is up for grabs from 2001.
</P>
<P>
The Premier League are still attempting to renegotiate the
contracts with the two men, while lawyers are investigating
whether they were legally binding as costly legal action could
ensue if they were unlawfully terminated.
</P>
<P>
The controversy led to Richards' initial interim appointment,
with the rules of association changed to allow an active club
chairman to also take over as Premier League chairman.
</P>
<P>
Sir John was not connected with any club and following the
permanent move, it is likely a review will be held in 12 months'
time as it is believed the League have not totally ruled out the
possibility of appointing another independent in the future.
</P>
<P>
Mike Foster retains his position as acting chief executive,
with the process of appointing somebody permanent having been
initiated at today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
In a Premier League statement, spokesman Mike Lee said: "Dave
Richards has agreed to serve as chairman for a further period to
provide stability and experience whilst a new chief executive is
appointed." 
</P>
</TEXT>
