<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Move Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks moved
higher Monday amid reports on worldwide PC sales rise and strong
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 28.92 at
10,718.59. Among the 30 Dow components, IBM's shares were up
sharply again after a big rally last week on a strong earnings
report while mining, manufacturing and consumer stocks were also
higher.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq index moved into record
territory as strong PC shipments reports renewed strength in
technology shares. The index rose 61.36 at 2,652.05, surpassing
its closing record high of 2,598.81, set on April 12.
</P>
<P>
International Data Corp. said that worldwide PC
shipments rose 19 percent in the first quarter of this year
while Gartner Group Ins.s Dataquest unit reported an increase of 17
percent. The reports pushed computer-related stocks higher.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 3.19 at 1,360.04 but
the NYSE index was down 0.47 at 638.83.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index rose 1.24 to
771.60 while the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose
3.24 to 434.97.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-6 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,398 up, 1,618 down and 537
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 706.61 million shares from 741.49
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
In a rare departure from the normal scramble on Wall Street,
trading was halted for one minute of silence at noon on the New
York Stock Exchange, American Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock
Market and Chicago Mercantile Exchange in memory of the
Colorado high school shooting victims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
