<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0380 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Reports 178 Refugees From Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Romania has granted so far the
status of refugees to 178 ethnic Serbians and Albanians coming in
from neighboring Yugoslavia, the national Rompres news agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The refugees were boarded in the western counties of Arad,
Mehedinti and Timis, as well as in the central counties of Sibiu
and Brasov and in the capital city of Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
The number of people arriving from Yugoslavia is in excess of
178, as many prefer to stay with their relatives or friends and
apply for the refugee status from western states.
</P>
<P>
According to Head of the Local Public Administration Department
Vlad Rosca, board and meal conditions for the refugees are "very
good." However, he complained that the allocated funds are
insufficient, and hoped more money will be diverted for this
purpose soon.
</P>
<P>
When the refugees began to get in across the Yugoslav border,
Romania showed itself willing to accommodate up to 6,000 people,
with financial support from international institutions. The money
required for the daily upkeep of one refugee ranges between 10 and
15 U.S. dollars daily, according to Foreign Minister Andrei Plesu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990427.0381 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICRC Chief Contacts 3 U.S. Prisoners of War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- President of the International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) Cornelio Sommaruga had a brief
meeting Monday with the three United States servicemen held by the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia since 31 March 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The Yugoslav authorities assured the ICRC that a full visit
could take place in accordance with the organization's standard
procedures tomorrow, 27 April, during which delegates will be
allowed to hold private talks with the prisoners and to register
their personal details," said the ICRC in a press release here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The POWs will also be able to reply to Red Cross messages from
their families that were handed over to them during Sommaruga's
visit, according to the ICRC.
</P>
<P>
"This meeting follows numerous representations made by the ICRC
to the Yugoslav federal authorities," said the ICRC. "The ICRC
appreciates this latest development, especially since it will
alleviate the anxiety of the prisoners' families."
</P>
<P>
The ICRC expressed hope that it could carry out a comprehensive
visit to the three POWs Tuesday, and to see them again during the
coming weeks and for as long as they are detained.
</P>
<P>
It also expects to have access to any other persons detained in
connection with the hostilities, as stipulated by the Geneva
Conventions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
